WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.320
[Amit Varma]: Ever since the farm bills were passed, I have been inundated with requests to do an episode

00:00:10.320 --> 00:00:14.960
[Amit Varma]: on them. One reason I took my time was that I was figuring them out myself. This is a

00:00:14.960 --> 00:00:20.360
[Amit Varma]: complex issue. There are many aspects to these bills. And to me, the big issue now is not

00:00:20.360 --> 00:00:24.480
[Amit Varma]: just the content of the bills, but the way in which they were pushed through, and then

00:00:24.480 --> 00:00:29.040
[Amit Varma]: the way in which our government is treating the protesting farmers. I've often said that

00:00:29.040 --> 00:00:34.320
[Amit Varma]: the end does not justify the means. And this is an illustration of that. Now I know that

00:00:34.320 --> 00:00:39.160
[Amit Varma]: nuance can sometimes be looked upon as hedging or straddling the fence. In these times where

00:00:39.160 --> 00:00:43.760
[Amit Varma]: so much of the discourse is polarized and partisan, there's pressure on everyone to

00:00:43.760 --> 00:00:49.640
[Amit Varma]: think only in terms of black and white. Pick a tribe and go with it. Don't evaluate each

00:00:49.640 --> 00:00:54.680
[Amit Varma]: issue on its own. But that's not me. So at the risk of all sides coming down hard on

00:00:54.680 --> 00:00:59.720
[Amit Varma]: me, let me just say that it's possible to hold a series of parallel thoughts on an issue

00:00:59.720 --> 00:01:04.280
[Amit Varma]: as complicated as this. I've written about agriculture for a couple of decades. I've

00:01:04.280 --> 00:01:08.080
[Amit Varma]: written about Indian politics for a couple of decades. I've done many episodes on both

00:01:08.080 --> 00:01:13.680
[Amit Varma]: subjects. And if I have to sum up what I feel about these farm bills from these two vantage

00:01:13.680 --> 00:01:18.560
[Amit Varma]: points, here's what I would say. One, while I have some quibbles with the content of the

00:01:18.560 --> 00:01:23.640
[Amit Varma]: bills, I think they go in the right direction. They empower farmers with choice without taking

00:01:23.640 --> 00:01:29.160
[Amit Varma]: anything away from them. Much of the rhetoric against these bills is unfounded and I discussed

00:01:29.160 --> 00:01:34.760
[Amit Varma]: some of it in this episode. However, the end doesn't justify the means. The way the government

00:01:34.760 --> 00:01:39.300
[Amit Varma]: pushed these bills through was disgraceful and I don't even have words to describe the

00:01:39.300 --> 00:01:44.120
[Amit Varma]: contemptible manner in which this government is treating the dissenting farmers. Dissent

00:01:44.120 --> 00:01:49.000
[Amit Varma]: is an important part of our democracy. The farmers have a right to protest and the government

00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:55.200
[Amit Varma]: needs to engage with them respectfully. Instead, the farmers have been called terrorists and

00:01:55.200 --> 00:02:00.560
[Amit Varma]: anti-nationals. While the reforms may have been crafted by some fine thinkers, the government's

00:02:00.560 --> 00:02:06.840
[Amit Varma]: strategy towards handling these protests seems to have been formulated by the IT cell. Statesmanship

00:02:06.840 --> 00:02:12.720
[Amit Varma]: could have solved this problem. Instead, we have thuggery of the most base kind. And this

00:02:12.720 --> 00:02:18.160
[Amit Varma]: question now comes to my mind. What's the point of trying to save agriculture if on

00:02:18.160 --> 00:02:24.440
[Amit Varma]: the way you damage our democracy?

00:02:24.440 --> 00:02:29.640
[Unknown]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics and behavioral

00:02:29.640 --> 00:02:36.560
[Amit Varma]: science. Please welcome your host, Amit Verma.

00:02:36.560 --> 00:02:40.720
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen. My guest today is Ajay Shah, co-author of the brilliant

00:02:40.720 --> 00:02:45.200
[Amit Varma]: book In Service of the Republic, on which I did a popular episode last year. In fact,

00:02:45.200 --> 00:02:49.700
[Amit Varma]: Ajay has been on the show a few times before and every time I speak to him, I feel like

00:02:49.700 --> 00:02:53.880
[Amit Varma]: my brain has expanded. I invited him on this episode because I came across some of his

00:02:53.880 --> 00:02:58.960
[Amit Varma]: writing on agriculture and as always was blown away by his clarity of thought. I've done

00:02:58.960 --> 00:03:03.440
[Amit Varma]: many episodes on agriculture myself, including with the farmer leader, Gunwant Patil, and

00:03:03.440 --> 00:03:07.200
[Amit Varma]: written a lot about it as well. All those episodes and essays will be linked in the

00:03:07.200 --> 00:03:11.840
[Amit Varma]: show notes. Now, before you begin listening to our conversation, I should warn you that

00:03:11.840 --> 00:03:17.840
[Amit Varma]: we only get to talking about the farm bills halfway through the episode. I enjoy discursive

00:03:17.840 --> 00:03:23.180
[Amit Varma]: conversations, especially with someone like Ajay, who is such a polymath. I enjoyed picking

00:03:23.180 --> 00:03:27.840
[Amit Varma]: his brain on a variety of subjects and we spent a fair bit of the first hour talking

00:03:27.840 --> 00:03:33.000
[Amit Varma]: about how he learns new subjects, his approach to knowledge management, how he's made himself

00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:37.440
[Amit Varma]: into a health economist over the last few months, the crucial difference between public

00:03:37.440 --> 00:03:41.920
[Amit Varma]: health and healthcare, how we could have tackled this pandemic differently, and what we can

00:03:41.920 --> 00:03:47.280
[Amit Varma]: still do moving forward. Much illumination. And I hope you enjoy this episode. But before

00:03:47.280 --> 00:03:53.120
[Amit Varma]: we begin, let's take a quick commercial break.

00:03:53.120 --> 00:03:57.280
[Amit Varma]: So I have a unique problem. This is a commercial break. And this week, I don't actually have

00:03:57.280 --> 00:04:01.040
[Amit Varma]: a commercial for you. I can't even plug the online courses I teach because they're closed

00:04:01.040 --> 00:04:05.720
[Amit Varma]: for registration right now. And they open again in March. So let me not sell anything

00:04:05.720 --> 00:04:11.600
[Amit Varma]: to you. But instead, express my gratitude at being such a committed bunch of listeners.

00:04:11.600 --> 00:04:15.560
[Amit Varma]: Social media can often be unpleasant and toxic. The level of discourse can be shallow and

00:04:15.560 --> 00:04:21.040
[Amit Varma]: angry. But whenever I interact with listeners of the show, I feel like I am in a good place.

00:04:21.040 --> 00:04:24.920
[Amit Varma]: Like me, you just want a good conversation. You're not looking at narratives that confirm

00:04:24.920 --> 00:04:29.600
[Amit Varma]: your beliefs. You're open to having your thinking challenged, and your worldview expanded. And

00:04:29.600 --> 00:04:34.040
[Amit Varma]: even when you disagree with me or my guest, you're not judgmental. We are not evil or

00:04:34.040 --> 00:04:38.680
[Amit Varma]: stupid because we hold different opinions. And while a podcast may seem like a one way

00:04:38.680 --> 00:04:43.200
[Amit Varma]: street, I produce content you listen. This is more than that to me. I feel like I am

00:04:43.200 --> 00:04:48.720
[Amit Varma]: one cog in a silent community of people who care about ideas and who acknowledge each

00:04:48.720 --> 00:04:54.160
[Amit Varma]: other's humanity. So while I usually say this at the end of my show, I'll also say it now.

00:04:54.160 --> 00:04:55.160
[Amit Varma]: Thank you for listening.

00:04:55.160 --> 00:05:00.040
[Amit Varma]: Ajay, welcome to the scene and the unseen.

00:05:00.040 --> 00:05:03.120
[Guest]: Thank you for having me here as always.

00:05:03.120 --> 00:05:07.120
[Amit Varma]: So tell me about, you know, your last few months, like when I invited you for the show,

00:05:07.120 --> 00:05:11.760
[Amit Varma]: you mentioned that at this moment in time, your primary hat is that of a health economist,

00:05:11.760 --> 00:05:16.080
[Amit Varma]: which took me a little bit by surprise or not too much by surprise, because you are

00:05:16.080 --> 00:05:21.480
[Amit Varma]: one of those economists who always kind of goes back to first principles and sort of

00:05:21.480 --> 00:05:26.000
[Amit Varma]: figuring out everything from there. So one would imagine that anything that you get interested

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:31.600
[Amit Varma]: in would be easy for you to figure out and, you know, hack, so to speak. So tell me how

00:05:31.600 --> 00:05:34.960
[Amit Varma]: your last few months have been. Have you been stuck at home during COVID? What have you

00:05:34.960 --> 00:05:39.720
[Amit Varma]: been doing? I hope you haven't actually caught it at any point. And intellectually, what

00:05:39.720 --> 00:05:42.360
[Amit Varma]: have you been thinking about? What are the problems that have interested you?

00:05:42.360 --> 00:05:49.040
[Guest]: No, I have not been got sick myself. I did get an antibody test once because somebody

00:05:49.040 --> 00:05:55.360
[Guest]: that I was with tested positive, but no, no luck so far in terms of getting sick. About

00:05:55.360 --> 00:06:01.200
[Guest]: five years ago, I had started working systematically in health economics. And so in some sense,

00:06:01.200 --> 00:06:07.520
[Guest]: by early 2020, my mind was ready for it. So my colleagues and I had done many, many things

00:06:07.520 --> 00:06:12.520
[Guest]: in the field of health. We had written an eclectic array of papers, mostly first principles,

00:06:12.520 --> 00:06:16.520
[Guest]: thinking of how you should think about health. You may have noticed that in the book that

00:06:16.520 --> 00:06:22.000
[Guest]: Vijay Kelkar and I wrote, one of the four chapters, which is a demo of applying this

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:27.560
[Guest]: conceptual framework was actually health. So that's an illustration of how we were approaching

00:06:27.560 --> 00:06:34.120
[Guest]: these things. And so in some sense, my mind was primed and ready for the story of COVID-19,

00:06:34.120 --> 00:06:40.680
[Guest]: which started unfolding from December 2019 onwards on the global consciousness, when

00:06:40.680 --> 00:06:45.840
[Guest]: we started seeing things happen first in China and then in Italy. I remember on the 6th of

00:06:45.840 --> 00:06:52.080
[Guest]: February, I wrote an article in the Business Standard, which has the title, dodging a bullet

00:06:52.080 --> 00:06:56.880
[Guest]: question mark, where I'm gently trying to say, guys, there's something big coming and

00:06:56.880 --> 00:07:04.040
[Guest]: potentially this could be pretty bad for us in India. By middle February, late February,

00:07:04.040 --> 00:07:09.800
[Guest]: my co-authors and I were writing a policy paper on what India should think about COVID-19.

00:07:09.800 --> 00:07:16.040
[Guest]: And it was considered a very alarmist paper at the time, because it did some simple mathematics

00:07:16.040 --> 00:07:22.040
[Guest]: of multiplying infection fatality rates observed elsewhere in the world into the number of

00:07:22.040 --> 00:07:27.880
[Guest]: people in India that might get infected. And then came the extremities of the lockdowns

00:07:27.880 --> 00:07:36.960
[Guest]: in late March. And I felt very nervous through those months about the tension between prevention

00:07:36.960 --> 00:07:42.760
[Guest]: and cure, that the Indian public health apparatus was really not up to it. So, you know, we

00:07:42.760 --> 00:07:48.920
[Guest]: were doing draconian things like a lockdown, and we were just not doing the genuine public

00:07:48.920 --> 00:07:53.720
[Guest]: health machinery, which in this case is contact tracing. What you need is a sophisticated

00:07:53.720 --> 00:07:58.400
[Guest]: health worker who will sit with an infected person and chat about what you were doing

00:07:58.400 --> 00:08:02.360
[Guest]: for the last one week, and find out all the people that you might have exposed, and then

00:08:02.360 --> 00:08:08.360
[Guest]: reach out to them, test them, and keep going forward. We didn't have that state capacity.

00:08:08.360 --> 00:08:14.600
[Guest]: We never built that state capacity. As usual in India, we had the technology delusion that

00:08:14.600 --> 00:08:19.360
[Guest]: we'll build some app and magically the problems of public policy will go away. And again,

00:08:19.360 --> 00:08:25.120
[Guest]: I thought that was not a very wise way to approach it. And side by side with that, the

00:08:25.120 --> 00:08:30.880
[Guest]: lockdowns were imposing costs on the economy, on livelihoods, on the working of the health

00:08:30.880 --> 00:08:36.960
[Guest]: care system. So I was watching that whole drama unfolding. And more recently, my colleagues

00:08:36.960 --> 00:08:42.160
[Guest]: and I have been working on trying to estimate the number of excess deaths that took place

00:08:42.160 --> 00:08:47.720
[Guest]: in the country. So I've been full of COVID-19 through all this. My last and most recent

00:08:47.720 --> 00:08:55.560
[Guest]: work has been on vaccines. And I feel reasonably uncomfortable with the state-led process for

00:08:55.560 --> 00:09:01.920
[Guest]: vaccines. Because in India, we don't have the government machinery to manage vaccination

00:09:01.920 --> 00:09:07.120
[Guest]: on a nationwide scale. It would be far more effective to let the self-organizing system

00:09:07.120 --> 00:09:13.920
[Guest]: figure it out. That we're holding many private vendors. There should be import of vaccines.

00:09:13.920 --> 00:09:19.000
[Guest]: And we should let firms and employers figure out how to get it to their employees. Let

00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:23.200
[Guest]: private health care companies work. And I feel we are needlessly trying to do a big

00:09:23.200 --> 00:09:28.440
[Guest]: centrally planned thing when we don't have the state capacity to do these things.

00:09:28.440 --> 00:09:34.160
[Guest]: So this has been the fun stuff I've been doing in the last one year. Precisely one year ago

00:09:34.160 --> 00:09:39.800
[Guest]: on February 5th is where I started on this subject. Because on the 6th of February, I

00:09:39.800 --> 00:09:41.000
[Guest]: have an article in the BS.

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:45.400
[Amit Varma]: To get a little meta, and you of course like to get meta with everything and so do I. So

00:09:45.400 --> 00:09:50.040
[Amit Varma]: to get a little meta about you, you know, when you approach a subject, what is the lens

00:09:50.040 --> 00:09:54.340
[Amit Varma]: through which you approach it? Like one lens which I've kind of started formulating for

00:09:54.340 --> 00:09:58.200
[Amit Varma]: myself when I start learning about something or thinking about something is what I call

00:09:58.200 --> 00:10:03.280
[Amit Varma]: the back and beyond framework, which is first I go back to first principles or root causes

00:10:03.280 --> 00:10:08.720
[Amit Varma]: and try to understand it through that. And then I think beyond first order effects and

00:10:08.720 --> 00:10:12.960
[Amit Varma]: so on and so forth. Now it strikes me that someone like you who you know, your book in

00:10:12.960 --> 00:10:18.120
[Amit Varma]: service of the Republic on which we did a very popular episode, has you doing exactly

00:10:18.120 --> 00:10:22.320
[Amit Varma]: the same thing to public policy kind of going back to first principles and so on. So is

00:10:22.320 --> 00:10:28.240
[Amit Varma]: that a discipline of thinking about a subject that you apply to everything that you come

00:10:28.240 --> 00:10:32.080
[Amit Varma]: across? For example, if you were to cook, would you again, go back to first principles

00:10:32.080 --> 00:10:36.440
[Amit Varma]: and try to figure things out that way? And that's question number one. And question number

00:10:36.440 --> 00:10:42.120
[Amit Varma]: two, what do you do for information assimilation? Because obviously, I'm assuming that you are

00:10:42.120 --> 00:10:47.240
[Amit Varma]: someone who reads a lot, you know, do you have specific tools for knowledge management?

00:10:47.240 --> 00:10:50.880
[Amit Varma]: How do you kind of organize everything that you're taking in?

00:10:50.880 --> 00:10:56.280
[Guest]: Many many things. So one at a time. In the world of public policy, my basic machinery

00:10:56.280 --> 00:11:02.000
[Guest]: is to have some intuition into the self organizing system. I think that is a single grand idea

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:08.360
[Guest]: that human beings are sentient, maximizing creatures and human beings will try to form

00:11:08.360 --> 00:11:16.560
[Guest]: solutions, will learn to work with each other and that there is more coordination and collaboration

00:11:16.560 --> 00:11:21.400
[Guest]: muscle that meets the eye. And human beings don't need to be told what to do. And public

00:11:21.400 --> 00:11:26.160
[Guest]: choice theory shows us how the telling human beings what to do very often goes wrong.

00:11:26.160 --> 00:11:31.440
[Guest]: Stepping a little away from public policy as a field. Oh, yes, I'm a science geek. I'm

00:11:31.440 --> 00:11:36.120
[Guest]: a researcher. I do everything as a research project. So every single thing that I do in

00:11:36.120 --> 00:11:41.840
[Guest]: life is the business of understanding it completely going down to first principles, reading research

00:11:41.840 --> 00:11:45.840
[Guest]: papers. So I'm blessed today that I can read research papers in almost any subject in the

00:11:45.840 --> 00:11:51.840
[Guest]: world that my broad knowledge today is such that I can read contemporary research articles

00:11:51.840 --> 00:11:56.880
[Guest]: and have some plausible level of understanding of essentially any field in the world.

00:11:56.880 --> 00:12:03.040
[Guest]: So my port of call for everything is Google Scholar. So my first search on most subjects

00:12:03.040 --> 00:12:07.160
[Guest]: is Google Scholar. I land up in Google Scholar. I start reading research papers and I can

00:12:07.160 --> 00:12:12.300
[Guest]: generally figure out things that are going on in a very wide area of fields. It could

00:12:12.300 --> 00:12:19.680
[Guest]: be gamma ray bursts and their impact on life on earth, or it could be Ayurvedic recipes

00:12:19.680 --> 00:12:26.240
[Guest]: for impacting on the immune system, or of course, economics, mathematics, statistics.

00:12:26.240 --> 00:12:31.600
[Guest]: You mentioned cooking. Yes, very much. I know a fair bit about food science. Then I apply

00:12:31.600 --> 00:12:38.600
[Guest]: my usual research recipes for innovation, which is a very standard trick and almost

00:12:38.600 --> 00:12:44.640
[Guest]: industrializable trick is to do combinatorial innovation. Okay. I consider it the trivialest

00:12:44.640 --> 00:12:47.920
[Guest]: thing in the world. I wonder why more people in the world don't do it. It roughly works

00:12:47.920 --> 00:12:53.160
[Guest]: like this, that if kajar halwa tastes pretty good with sugar, then maybe we should experiment

00:12:53.160 --> 00:12:59.840
[Guest]: with all the other sweeteners out there that try jaggery, try maple syrup, try honey. Okay.

00:12:59.840 --> 00:13:05.880
[Guest]: And see which of them works better. So it's just a analogies technology of rolling out

00:13:05.880 --> 00:13:11.120
[Guest]: many variants and picking one that works reasonably well. So this is an almost trivial way to

00:13:11.120 --> 00:13:16.160
[Guest]: innovate in any field that when we were in this situation in another field, we found

00:13:16.160 --> 00:13:21.120
[Guest]: that X approach worked reasonably well. Why don't we try that here? So that's where breadth

00:13:21.120 --> 00:13:26.460
[Guest]: is a great asset. Whereas narrow technical specialists tend to not be able to make those

00:13:26.460 --> 00:13:33.240
[Guest]: analogies of pulling in ideas from other fields. Finally, my recipe for learning new fields.

00:13:33.240 --> 00:13:37.320
[Guest]: So I said that about five years ago, I started doing health. My standard recipe for starting

00:13:37.320 --> 00:13:43.760
[Guest]: a new field is to first play on adjacencies. So I recognized five years ago that I'm not

00:13:43.760 --> 00:13:48.720
[Guest]: an expert on health, but I was an expert on many connected things. So as an example, I

00:13:48.720 --> 00:13:54.000
[Guest]: knew a lot about finance. So natural place to go was, can we learn about health insurance?

00:13:54.000 --> 00:14:01.240
[Guest]: Okay. And the entire FSLRC technology is a great way to understand IRDA and health insurance

00:14:01.240 --> 00:14:07.200
[Guest]: and government run health insurance programs. And so that's a natural way to make inroads

00:14:07.200 --> 00:14:13.760
[Guest]: into a new field, which is take the adjacencies. Similarly, as simple technology that my colleagues

00:14:13.760 --> 00:14:18.920
[Guest]: and I do better than most is to work with data, is to statistically analyze data, is

00:14:18.920 --> 00:14:24.400
[Guest]: to be able to understand what's going on in large complex datasets. So we have been pioneers

00:14:24.400 --> 00:14:30.000
[Guest]: in putting big datasets to work on understanding health and we managed to get many interesting

00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:35.320
[Guest]: innovations out of that. So this is on how to approach a new field. And finally, you

00:14:35.320 --> 00:14:42.800
[Guest]: talked about information management. I think that there is only one, okay, maybe two, three

00:14:42.800 --> 00:14:49.320
[Guest]: non-standard things that I do. The first is that my prime source of the flow of new information

00:14:49.320 --> 00:14:56.360
[Guest]: is RSS. So good old fashioned RSS feed reader that I'm highly selective about what feeds

00:14:56.360 --> 00:15:00.560
[Guest]: I subscribe to. I have about 100 feeds that I subscribe to, and they are my window in

00:15:00.560 --> 00:15:05.800
[Guest]: the world. And my second recipe is that I'm generally not looking at anything in the world

00:15:05.800 --> 00:15:11.280
[Guest]: of social media, so that I try to protect myself from the noise and stay connected to

00:15:11.280 --> 00:15:16.440
[Guest]: the deeper things. So I take journal articles seriously. I read working papers, I read blogs.

00:15:16.440 --> 00:15:19.920
[Guest]: I think this is the way to keep sane in the modern world.

00:15:19.920 --> 00:15:24.640
[Amit Varma]: Right. And you mentioned about how, you know, you got into health economics five years ago.

00:15:24.640 --> 00:15:26.760
[Amit Varma]: For the benefit of my listeners, what is health economics?

00:15:26.760 --> 00:15:32.240
[Guest]: Health economics is the study of the causes and consequences of sickness and health. So

00:15:32.240 --> 00:15:38.920
[Guest]: we'd like to understand from cradle to grave, people being born, people achieving the full

00:15:38.920 --> 00:15:49.240
[Guest]: potentiality of height and strength as adults about experiences with sickness, about what

00:15:49.240 --> 00:15:54.840
[Guest]: determines death, and the whole interaction between prevention and cure about a problem

00:15:54.840 --> 00:16:01.520
[Guest]: like air quality that is damaging the health of people in very fundamental ways. And also

00:16:01.520 --> 00:16:05.320
[Guest]: the whole health care process that you get sick, you try to go to a provider, you try

00:16:05.320 --> 00:16:10.840
[Guest]: to get better and the whole incentives of how the health care industry treats each of

00:16:10.840 --> 00:16:15.920
[Guest]: us and what generates good and bad outcomes in the behavior of health care. So this is

00:16:15.920 --> 00:16:20.560
[Guest]: cradle to grave understanding the causes and consequences of our health, that is health

00:16:20.560 --> 00:16:21.960
[Amit Varma]: economics.

00:16:21.960 --> 00:16:26.000
[Amit Varma]: And one of the things I've noticed about, you know, the last few months in various domains

00:16:26.000 --> 00:16:30.560
[Amit Varma]: is that there are many things that are normalized and you kind of take them for granted, but

00:16:30.560 --> 00:16:35.360
[Amit Varma]: then there is a crisis and those things come to stark attention, they kind of stand out

00:16:35.360 --> 00:16:39.880
[Amit Varma]: more because of the crisis, while earlier they were, in a sense, normalized, like I

00:16:39.880 --> 00:16:44.280
[Amit Varma]: just recently did an episode with an activist called Ruben Mascarena. So, you know, did

00:16:44.280 --> 00:16:49.280
[Amit Varma]: a Khana Chahiye campaign in Bombay, where there was an explosion of hunger in the streets.

00:16:49.280 --> 00:16:54.640
[Amit Varma]: And one of the things that it brought into stark relief is what a large number of Indians

00:16:54.640 --> 00:16:59.800
[Amit Varma]: are actually living such precarious lives that just one crisis, one emergency can send

00:16:59.800 --> 00:17:03.720
[Amit Varma]: them toppling over the edge into something as stark as, you know, not knowing where the

00:17:03.720 --> 00:17:07.360
[Amit Varma]: next meal is going to come from. And that's just one context, which immediately comes

00:17:07.360 --> 00:17:11.240
[Amit Varma]: to mind because of just on that episode. But, you know, over the last few months, if you

00:17:11.240 --> 00:17:17.280
[Amit Varma]: had to look at both health economics and otherwise our economy, are there aspects like that,

00:17:17.280 --> 00:17:22.560
[Amit Varma]: which you think came to the stark attention of policymakers and thinkers, which they might

00:17:22.560 --> 00:17:25.320
[Amit Varma]: otherwise have glossed over earlier?

00:17:25.320 --> 00:17:31.920
[Guest]: So I think that in the balance between public health and healthcare, there has been learning

00:17:31.920 --> 00:17:38.440
[Guest]: in India. I think that when Kelkar and I wrote that chapter on health in the book, it was

00:17:38.440 --> 00:17:44.160
[Guest]: reasonably heretical. Almost the entire Indian health policy establishment looked at the

00:17:44.160 --> 00:17:49.720
[Guest]: world from the vantage point of being a doctor. The doctor says, I don't care why, but you

00:17:49.720 --> 00:17:54.880
[Guest]: got sick and you landed in front of me and I want the adequate resourcing and I want

00:17:54.880 --> 00:18:00.120
[Guest]: to get paid well in return for fixing you up. So that was the worldview of health policy

00:18:00.120 --> 00:18:04.640
[Guest]: in India, that people get sick and we're not responsible and we don't care why people get

00:18:04.640 --> 00:18:09.280
[Guest]: sick and we just want to put more and more money into fixing up the sick people that

00:18:09.280 --> 00:18:15.720
[Guest]: come my way. I think COVID-19 has done well in waking up the community that there is a

00:18:15.720 --> 00:18:21.480
[Guest]: very big distinction between healthcare versus public health, between prevention and cure.

00:18:21.480 --> 00:18:26.520
[Guest]: And prevention is a thousand times better than cure. I could go on and on. One day we

00:18:26.520 --> 00:18:31.760
[Guest]: should sit over dinner and I would like to show you the full practical economic and moral

00:18:31.760 --> 00:18:38.000
[Guest]: argument that there's really something profoundly important in doing more on prevention. That

00:18:38.000 --> 00:18:43.120
[Guest]: argument is further amplified in India, given the fact that the healthcare is reasonably

00:18:43.120 --> 00:18:49.720
[Guest]: broken. So, you know, if you were in the UK and the NHS works reasonably well, even there,

00:18:49.720 --> 00:18:54.520
[Guest]: I would make a moral and practical argument in favor of prevention and not cure. It's

00:18:54.520 --> 00:19:00.440
[Guest]: a thousand times better to have a person not get diabetes or not get COVID-19, as opposed

00:19:00.440 --> 00:19:05.040
[Guest]: to trying to send them into a healthcare system. But in India, given that the healthcare system

00:19:05.040 --> 00:19:09.560
[Guest]: is pretty terrible, even for people like you and me, even for the richest people in India,

00:19:09.560 --> 00:19:14.920
[Guest]: healthcare in India does not work well. It's a really bad healthcare system. Then the importance

00:19:14.920 --> 00:19:20.560
[Guest]: of prevention is further amplified. That really the best of all worlds is one where people

00:19:20.560 --> 00:19:25.680
[Guest]: don't get sick. So as I read the budget speech yesterday, I was actually a bit delighted

00:19:25.680 --> 00:19:33.080
[Guest]: that I saw a lot of effort on questions that I classify as prevention. The only significant

00:19:33.080 --> 00:19:37.320
[Guest]: funding surge in a health related thing is on water and sanitation, which I think is

00:19:37.320 --> 00:19:42.360
[Guest]: absolutely fantastic. You know, it's much better that people get clean drinking water

00:19:42.360 --> 00:19:48.960
[Guest]: and that there is better handling of sewage. I see effort on building the NCDC, which is

00:19:48.960 --> 00:19:54.280
[Guest]: a bit like an Indian take on the U.S. CDC, which is absolutely fantastic. We need to

00:19:54.280 --> 00:20:00.240
[Guest]: get better on how we think about communicable disease. And we actually do not see significant

00:20:00.240 --> 00:20:06.120
[Guest]: increases in the spending on the standard machinery of healthcare. So as I read the

00:20:06.120 --> 00:20:13.000
[Guest]: budget speech and some of my colleagues and collaborators worked through the numbers in

00:20:13.000 --> 00:20:20.640
[Guest]: the budget, it did feel like there was fresh emphasis on prevention, on public health,

00:20:20.640 --> 00:20:26.880
[Guest]: as opposed to healthcare. And these, even these basic words, the distinction that in

00:20:26.880 --> 00:20:30.920
[Guest]: health policy, there are two rooms in the house, there's prevention and there's cure,

00:20:30.920 --> 00:20:35.280
[Guest]: but there's public health and there is healthcare. These things are not widely known in India.

00:20:35.280 --> 00:20:41.920
[Guest]: And I feel this last one year has generated fresh thinking and questioning in the minds

00:20:41.920 --> 00:20:47.520
[Guest]: of many people. And I think years from now, we might well call this an important year

00:20:47.520 --> 00:20:49.520
[Guest]: in getting our heads in the right place.

00:20:49.520 --> 00:20:53.880
[Amit Varma]: Wow. And just to clarify for the listeners, the sort of difference between public health

00:20:53.880 --> 00:20:58.120
[Amit Varma]: and healthcare, I'll go back to an analogy that I think you had made. I forget on what

00:20:58.120 --> 00:21:02.800
[Amit Varma]: fora it is, maybe you were replying to someone on one of your rare visits to Twitter, but

00:21:02.800 --> 00:21:06.480
[Amit Varma]: it was essentially that, you know, if it comes to the problem of malaria, then you think

00:21:06.480 --> 00:21:11.880
[Amit Varma]: of public health as doing public fogging so that mosquitoes don't occur in the first place.

00:21:11.880 --> 00:21:15.520
[Amit Varma]: Whereas healthcare would be, you know, the doctor treating the patient who's already

00:21:15.520 --> 00:21:19.600
[Amit Varma]: got malaria. And your point was that, you know, taking care of the public health, just

00:21:19.600 --> 00:21:23.400
[Amit Varma]: making sure the mosquitoes aren't there in the first place, so nobody gets malaria is

00:21:23.400 --> 00:21:27.840
[Amit Varma]: the way to go. Except one would imagine that why is a politician incentivized to do that?

00:21:27.840 --> 00:21:33.080
[Amit Varma]: Because, you know, whatever good comes out of it is essentially unseen. So it's interesting

00:21:33.080 --> 00:21:37.160
[Amit Varma]: that you point out that, you know, in this budget, they are paying attention to it. And

00:21:37.160 --> 00:21:41.640
[Amit Varma]: I guess in the case of COVID, that would mean when you talk about prevention, one is of

00:21:41.640 --> 00:21:46.720
[Amit Varma]: course, a draconian blunt tool of a lockdown. But other similar ways of promoting public

00:21:46.720 --> 00:21:50.840
[Amit Varma]: health would be just making sure everybody gets a mask and all of those things, I guess,

00:21:50.840 --> 00:21:51.840
[Guest]: right?

00:21:51.840 --> 00:21:56.560
[Guest]: The most important piece which was absent in India is contact tracing. So when you test

00:21:56.560 --> 00:22:01.240
[Guest]: positive, a health worker should come sit with you and chat about your last one week.

00:22:01.240 --> 00:22:04.720
[Guest]: It needs to be a sophisticated, intelligent conversation. Where were you? What were you

00:22:04.720 --> 00:22:10.800
[Guest]: doing? Who were you with? Then identify 10-20 people that you had significant exposure with,

00:22:10.800 --> 00:22:14.120
[Guest]: and then go meet each of those people, test each of those people. And that's how you keep

00:22:14.120 --> 00:22:18.440
[Guest]: the chains going. That's called contact tracing. And it is completely absent in India.

00:22:18.440 --> 00:22:23.040
[Amit Varma]: You know, that's good in theory, but it strikes me that, and I'm of course a cynic of straight

00:22:23.040 --> 00:22:27.160
[Amit Varma]: capacity, but it just strikes me that given the scale, given how fast things were spreading,

00:22:27.160 --> 00:22:30.120
[Amit Varma]: that there was simply no state capacity to do that anyway, you know.

00:22:30.120 --> 00:22:33.760
[Guest]: Sure. I agree with you that we did not have that state capacity in India. But if you ask

00:22:33.760 --> 00:22:37.880
[Guest]: me, what do you need by way of health policy? This is what you need. And, you know, should

00:22:37.880 --> 00:22:42.080
[Guest]: we spend the next 20 years figuring out how to do this? Because there will be other pandemics

00:22:42.080 --> 00:22:48.200
[Guest]: in the future? I feel yes. And this is not an Arogya Setu problem. So once again, the

00:22:48.200 --> 00:22:53.000
[Guest]: technological solutionism got us in the exactly wrong place. I feel that for many policy makers,

00:22:53.000 --> 00:22:57.640
[Guest]: it was convenient and comfortable to say, yeah, I've covered that because we've got

00:22:57.640 --> 00:23:02.400
[Guest]: this Arogya Setu thing. And this is something that's happening very often in the Indian

00:23:02.400 --> 00:23:08.760
[Guest]: public policy landscape, that we tend to think of technology as the main solution, whereas

00:23:08.760 --> 00:23:14.680
[Guest]: technology is a small part of complex organization problems, of complex public ad problems.

00:23:14.680 --> 00:23:19.960
[Guest]: If you think of any private business and you think of doing a business process re-engineering,

00:23:19.960 --> 00:23:25.440
[Guest]: 99% of the problem in business process re-engineering is thinking about the organization, is dealing

00:23:25.440 --> 00:23:30.440
[Guest]: with internal political battles of changing the organization structure and getting people

00:23:30.440 --> 00:23:36.400
[Guest]: to go along with a new process design. And 1% of the problem is some technology. So yeah,

00:23:36.400 --> 00:23:40.280
[Guest]: technology is important, but it's really a tiny part of the problem. And when we push

00:23:40.280 --> 00:23:45.280
[Guest]: a technology first approach, we tend to cut corners on the really important and really

00:23:45.280 --> 00:23:49.880
[Guest]: difficult things in India, which is the public administration, the management, the organization

00:23:49.880 --> 00:23:52.720
[Guest]: design, the changing the processes of government.

00:23:52.720 --> 00:23:57.720
[Amit Varma]: I mean, would it be the case that for whoever is in charge of doing things, a politician

00:23:57.720 --> 00:24:02.600
[Amit Varma]: or the bureaucrats concerned or whatever, it comes to a point of not just doing something,

00:24:02.600 --> 00:24:06.720
[Amit Varma]: but in a very complex landscape of being able to show that, yes, we are on it, we are doing

00:24:06.720 --> 00:24:12.120
[Amit Varma]: something. And in those senses, you know, Arogya Setu is like a very visible thing that

00:24:12.120 --> 00:24:16.200
[Amit Varma]: we are on it, we are getting technology to work for us, whereas going the hard yards

00:24:16.200 --> 00:24:20.320
[Amit Varma]: of building that kind of intricate state capacity where you have, where you train people to

00:24:20.320 --> 00:24:25.400
[Amit Varma]: actually, you know, ask the right questions and begin that kind of contract tracing, that

00:24:25.400 --> 00:24:28.120
[Amit Varma]: seems like an enormously huge task to do so.

00:24:28.120 --> 00:24:32.920
[Guest]: So then it turns to what are the, so public choice theory shows us that every politician,

00:24:32.920 --> 00:24:41.640
[Guest]: every official is maximizing for themselves. And if we live in a country with low standards

00:24:41.640 --> 00:24:48.800
[Guest]: of public discourse, and if rolling out an Arogya Setu suffices to claim that I did a

00:24:48.800 --> 00:24:51.600
[Guest]: good job, then yeah, that's all that they will do.

00:24:51.600 --> 00:24:57.320
[Guest]: Whereas to the extent that the politicians and officials are held accountable for the

00:24:57.320 --> 00:25:03.240
[Guest]: actual spread of COVID-19 in the country, then that could change things. So, you know,

00:25:03.240 --> 00:25:08.560
[Guest]: India has some of the highest seroprevalence rates in the world, which shows that basically

00:25:08.560 --> 00:25:13.640
[Guest]: the disease just ran, nevermind the lockdowns, nevermind the Arogya Setu, the disease just

00:25:13.640 --> 00:25:20.760
[Guest]: ran free in India more than essentially anywhere else in the world. And to the extent that

00:25:20.760 --> 00:25:27.880
[Guest]: the people will hold government officials and politicians accountable for that environment

00:25:27.880 --> 00:25:33.880
[Guest]: of the spread of the disease, then it will generate incentives for the politicians and

00:25:33.880 --> 00:25:35.400
[Guest]: officials to behave differently.

00:25:35.400 --> 00:25:42.160
[Amit Varma]: My sort of brief thought on that is that one, there is a very sort of complex decision-making

00:25:42.160 --> 00:25:45.600
[Amit Varma]: landscape where pretty much no matter what you do, whether you have a lockdown or don't

00:25:45.600 --> 00:25:49.240
[Amit Varma]: have a lockdown or to what extent you have one, you know, the seen effects are pretty

00:25:49.240 --> 00:25:53.800
[Amit Varma]: bad, which is the lives that are lost or the damage done to the economy. The unseen effects,

00:25:53.800 --> 00:25:58.640
[Amit Varma]: which is the lives that would have been lost in the counterfactual are kind of invisible.

00:25:58.640 --> 00:26:01.640
[Amit Varma]: So it's like a very difficult choice to make. You're going to get hammered no matter what

00:26:01.640 --> 00:26:06.440
[Amit Varma]: you do and perhaps unfairly hammered if you took something close to an optimal decision.

00:26:06.440 --> 00:26:10.360
[Amit Varma]: And the other aspect of what I see in India today when you talk about accountability is

00:26:10.360 --> 00:26:15.480
[Amit Varma]: that rather than see citizens in search of holding the government accountable, which

00:26:15.480 --> 00:26:20.240
[Amit Varma]: is very hard, especially in such a complex scenario where not everybody or not anybody

00:26:20.240 --> 00:26:24.240
[Amit Varma]: perhaps can really figure out what the counterfactuals would have looked like, there is also the

00:26:24.240 --> 00:26:30.120
[Amit Varma]: tendency in India of picking your tribe and then just going with, you know, whatever your

00:26:30.120 --> 00:26:34.840
[Amit Varma]: tribe does is good. Whatever the other tribe does is bad by default. And, you know, we'll

00:26:34.840 --> 00:26:38.400
[Amit Varma]: talk a little bit about the farm bills later on in this episode. And it seems to me that

00:26:38.400 --> 00:26:42.800
[Amit Varma]: that's also happened with the farm bills in the sense that those who've picked one tribe

00:26:42.800 --> 00:26:47.960
[Amit Varma]: is that the Modi government can do no good. And those who pick the other tribe is that,

00:26:47.960 --> 00:26:51.840
[Amit Varma]: you know, it doesn't matter what the means of pushing this through or whatever, the Modi

00:26:51.840 --> 00:26:56.720
[Amit Varma]: government can do only good. So it seems to me that a lot of, and perhaps these are the

00:26:56.720 --> 00:27:01.280
[Amit Varma]: vocal minorities, which appear to be like this, and the silent majority hasn't actually

00:27:01.280 --> 00:27:07.560
[Amit Varma]: picked a tribe and is open to these questions, and so on. But, you know, because of these

00:27:07.560 --> 00:27:13.320
[Amit Varma]: sort of dual problems, one is just the epistemic problem of figuring out whether this action

00:27:13.320 --> 00:27:17.960
[Amit Varma]: was right or wrong, because we cannot know the counterfactual and the tribal instinct.

00:27:17.960 --> 00:27:24.600
[Amit Varma]: I'm not so, I mean, holding governments accountable, then just sounds very nice in theory, but

00:27:24.600 --> 00:27:26.840
[Guest]: I mean, does it really happen?

00:27:26.840 --> 00:27:34.840
[Guest]: Our only hope in hell as a society is the idea that there will be a republic where there

00:27:34.840 --> 00:27:41.240
[Guest]: will be checks and balances, where governments will be held accountable, and then we will

00:27:41.240 --> 00:27:45.480
[Guest]: get performance. Because if that breaks down, then you know, we're toast, there will be

00:27:45.480 --> 00:27:52.600
[Guest]: no future of any prosperity and freedom and creativity. If we don't get there. I totally

00:27:52.600 --> 00:28:00.640
[Guest]: agree with what you're saying that tribalism and the screaming of the electronic age has

00:28:00.640 --> 00:28:07.160
[Guest]: replaced rational thinking. And for all of us, it seems to me that this is really a big

00:28:07.160 --> 00:28:14.160
[Guest]: aspect of what we should be up to in life, which is to step away from the screaming and

00:28:14.160 --> 00:28:22.760
[Guest]: the mudslinging and the just sheer ugliness of the electronic age and create safe spaces

00:28:22.760 --> 00:28:29.960
[Guest]: for careful, thorough, sensible conversation. I mean, it seems like an unreal ask, but it

00:28:29.960 --> 00:28:35.360
[Guest]: is the need of the age that this is what all of us need. And we need to do less screaming

00:28:35.360 --> 00:28:40.680
[Guest]: and less mudslinging and just be quiet and be thorough, work harder, think harder. The

00:28:40.680 --> 00:28:44.360
[Guest]: world is a complicated place and we need more knowledge, not less.

00:28:44.360 --> 00:28:47.880
[Amit Varma]: And you know, and I think there is a constituency for that. And it's much larger than we think.

00:28:47.880 --> 00:28:52.000
[Amit Varma]: It's just very silent. So in all the Twitter shouting, you don't really notice it. But

00:28:52.000 --> 00:28:55.800
[Amit Varma]: I think I see some of it in, you know, the people who listen to my podcast, and I'm sure

00:28:55.800 --> 00:29:00.240
[Amit Varma]: the people who read your writing and there are people who are constantly searching for

00:29:00.240 --> 00:29:04.960
[Amit Varma]: that kind of insight. Now let's, as this is a show which takes many digressions, let's

00:29:04.960 --> 00:29:07.000
[Amit Varma]: take a quick digression. You mentioned

00:29:07.000 --> 00:29:13.040
[Guest]: I just want to say that you remember when we first started recording podcasts, it took

00:29:13.040 --> 00:29:19.200
[Guest]: me two whole podcast episodes to settle down and relax and talk to you because I was just

00:29:19.200 --> 00:29:24.400
[Guest]: so convinced I had, I was making assumptions that you're looking for snappy soundbites.

00:29:24.400 --> 00:29:29.760
[Guest]: And it took me a long time to get comfortable that no, you're not actually looking for snappy

00:29:29.760 --> 00:29:36.360
[Guest]: soundbites and that on this podcast platform, we have an audience that is interested in,

00:29:36.360 --> 00:29:39.840
[Guest]: you know, comfortable, reasonable, sane, quiet conversation.

00:29:39.840 --> 00:29:44.560
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, yeah. And that's honestly, it's not that it took you time to figure that out.

00:29:44.560 --> 00:29:50.200
[Amit Varma]: It took me time to figure it out and took like many, many tens of episodes to sort of

00:29:50.200 --> 00:29:55.200
[Amit Varma]: find this groove and realize that a lot of people crave sort of nuanced conversations.

00:29:55.200 --> 00:29:58.600
[Amit Varma]: But to stop patting myself on the back for a moment, I remember, you know, you mentioned

00:29:58.600 --> 00:30:02.440
[Amit Varma]: the budget. And I remember last year at around when the budget came out, you know, you, me

00:30:02.440 --> 00:30:05.780
[Amit Varma]: and Vivek called it an episode and I think you were in Mumbai only for a day and those

00:30:05.780 --> 00:30:09.040
[Amit Varma]: were pre-COVID times when we were recording in physical studios.

00:30:09.040 --> 00:30:12.680
[Amit Varma]: So I remember, you know, because you were in and out of Mumbai, I had the notice of

00:30:12.680 --> 00:30:18.040
[Amit Varma]: a day to organize a studio for our recording. My regular studio was booked out and I, you

00:30:18.040 --> 00:30:22.760
[Amit Varma]: know, opened, I guess the internet version of the Yellow Pages. I just went to Google

00:30:22.760 --> 00:30:28.840
[Amit Varma]: and I did search for recording studio Mumbai and the 23rd studio I called happened to have

00:30:28.840 --> 00:30:35.240
[Amit Varma]: a slot available. And we went to this random place, recorded, paid cash, got out. And,

00:30:35.240 --> 00:30:38.240
[Amit Varma]: you know, and I was thinking, what an amazing world that you can do something like this.

00:30:38.240 --> 00:30:41.800
[Amit Varma]: And before this recording, you mentioned what an amazing world that we can do something

00:30:41.800 --> 00:30:48.560
[Amit Varma]: like this, where, you know, we can remotely record with reasonably good technology and

00:30:48.560 --> 00:30:52.680
[Amit Varma]: from entirely kind of different places. So we're not really very far. I'm in Andheri,

00:30:52.680 --> 00:30:57.480
[Amit Varma]: you're in Karjat right now, I believe, but in these COVID times, that's a universal way.

00:30:57.480 --> 00:31:02.920
[Amit Varma]: So let me quickly ask for, you know, your sort of one minute recap of the budget, because

00:31:02.920 --> 00:31:07.200
[Amit Varma]: I won't actually be doing a budget special episode, but you mentioned that one aspect

00:31:07.200 --> 00:31:11.680
[Amit Varma]: of it that you liked is the focus on public health as opposed to health care in terms

00:31:11.680 --> 00:31:16.600
[Amit Varma]: of prevention, water, sanitation, all of those. But what are your broad sort of takeaways

00:31:16.600 --> 00:31:19.160
[Guest]: without getting into details?

00:31:19.160 --> 00:31:25.320
[Guest]: I'm delighted that the words privatizing PSU Bank has been used for the first time in India's

00:31:25.320 --> 00:31:31.800
[Guest]: history. Words matter. You break through these holy cows, it has consequences. So I'm delighted

00:31:31.800 --> 00:31:38.560
[Guest]: that that has happened. I'm also delighted about removing the FDI cap in insurance. I

00:31:38.560 --> 00:31:44.160
[Guest]: am not that excited about the extent to which these things are really the choke point in

00:31:44.160 --> 00:31:50.680
[Guest]: India's journey today, but they have come to become symbols of something and it's good

00:31:50.680 --> 00:31:57.440
[Guest]: to break through them. So in these respects, I was really happy at what I saw in the budget.

00:31:57.440 --> 00:32:04.120
[Guest]: I'm reasonably worried about what we are seeing on financial economic policy. We're seeing

00:32:04.120 --> 00:32:08.880
[Guest]: a whole bunch of 1970s and 1980s thinking. They want to set up a development finance

00:32:08.880 --> 00:32:12.720
[Guest]: institution. They want to set up a bad bank. They want to set up some government organization

00:32:12.720 --> 00:32:16.880
[Guest]: that will be the market maker for corporate bonds. This is not how it's done. This is

00:32:16.880 --> 00:32:22.760
[Guest]: not how it will work. And we have quite a financial crisis on our hands and this is

00:32:22.760 --> 00:32:29.160
[Guest]: not going to get fixed. I was delighted at the improvements in the transparency and the

00:32:29.160 --> 00:32:35.360
[Guest]: truthfulness of the budget statements that partly last year and partly this year, they've

00:32:35.360 --> 00:32:40.000
[Guest]: really done it. They have cleaned out the reporting. So for years and years, there was

00:32:40.000 --> 00:32:48.440
[Guest]: all kinds of obfuscation, bordering on prevarication that was happening in the financial statements

00:32:48.440 --> 00:32:53.200
[Guest]: being released by the government. This year, it feels like we're done. They've put everything

00:32:53.200 --> 00:32:59.520
[Guest]: on the table and it is being recorded and reported truthfully. Some people are jumping

00:32:59.520 --> 00:33:04.920
[Guest]: about the double quotes, large fiscal deficit. No, it's not a large fiscal deficit. It's

00:33:04.920 --> 00:33:11.160
[Guest]: just being reported. All that's changed is the reporting. It was there. It was lurking

00:33:11.160 --> 00:33:16.520
[Guest]: in a subclinical way for many years and we were just not talking about it as honestly

00:33:16.520 --> 00:33:22.920
[Guest]: and openly. So I felt some things are in a good direction. Some things are not. And the

00:33:22.920 --> 00:33:29.900
[Guest]: really, really big question, the trillion dollar question is, what will it take to change

00:33:29.900 --> 00:33:35.120
[Guest]: the investment climate in India to get the private sector back to buoyancy and optimism?

00:33:35.120 --> 00:33:40.400
[Guest]: And I think that turns on some of these central planning problems and rule of law problems.

00:33:40.400 --> 00:33:43.720
[Guest]: And I did not see a whole lot of that in the budget speech.

00:33:43.720 --> 00:33:50.520
[Amit Varma]: So, tell me another thing to continue down this digressive path that we look to the government

00:33:50.520 --> 00:33:56.000
[Amit Varma]: for reforms. We look to the budget to see what has been done, what has not been done

00:33:56.000 --> 00:34:00.120
[Amit Varma]: and are we moving ahead and all of that. But the thing is that in many of these cases,

00:34:00.120 --> 00:34:04.240
[Amit Varma]: politicians don't have deep knowledge of all of this and very often even bureaucrats are

00:34:04.240 --> 00:34:09.940
[Amit Varma]: generalists and kind of don't. So there is in the background, a community of experts

00:34:09.940 --> 00:34:14.840
[Amit Varma]: and elite influencers and economists and so on who work for years to kind of make things

00:34:14.840 --> 00:34:19.440
[Amit Varma]: happen behind the scenes till something that they've been talking about, you know, 20 years

00:34:19.440 --> 00:34:24.800
[Amit Varma]: ago finally comes into some bill or becomes a reform somewhere. And it's kind of like

00:34:24.800 --> 00:34:30.240
[Amit Varma]: a very silent effort. There's not much self-interest involved because these are not like industry

00:34:30.240 --> 00:34:34.240
[Amit Varma]: lobbies lobbying for a particular measure that will help them. Instead, it's just an

00:34:34.240 --> 00:34:38.520
[Amit Varma]: economist who doesn't directly benefit saying, hey, this is what the country needs. And a

00:34:38.520 --> 00:34:43.600
[Amit Varma]: lot of that kind of happens behind the scenes and you have yourself, you know, as part of

00:34:43.600 --> 00:34:47.760
[Amit Varma]: the finance ministry and the NIPFP and all of that sort of been a part of this group

00:34:47.760 --> 00:34:53.040
[Amit Varma]: of influencers trying to push change through and all of that. So one is kind of tell me

00:34:53.040 --> 00:34:58.240
[Amit Varma]: a little bit about this process about, you know, what are your incentives at play or

00:34:58.240 --> 00:35:04.120
[Amit Varma]: the incentives of all of these people who try to bring about change in this manner and

00:35:04.120 --> 00:35:09.480
[Amit Varma]: how does the process flow and how do you get people to listen to you? So there is a very

00:35:09.480 --> 00:35:15.680
[Guest]: well-defined process flow. In every field, you start at facts, you start at statistics.

00:35:15.680 --> 00:35:21.240
[Guest]: Okay. So the first puzzle in every field is that we in India need to establish some mechanisms

00:35:21.240 --> 00:35:25.840
[Guest]: of gathering data and systematizing the capture of data so that year after year after year,

00:35:25.840 --> 00:35:31.960
[Guest]: some good quality facts, micro data sets are being created. Then step two, you need a research

00:35:31.960 --> 00:35:36.360
[Guest]: community that will work on this data and that research community needs to be deeply

00:35:36.360 --> 00:35:42.440
[Guest]: rooted in India. So there is one problem of trying to get some papers through into journals

00:35:42.440 --> 00:35:47.560
[Guest]: abroad versus there's a different problem of trying to look at India, understand problems

00:35:47.560 --> 00:35:53.160
[Guest]: and contribute to knowledge here in India. So the extent to which many academics have

00:35:53.160 --> 00:35:58.920
[Guest]: become publish and perish looking at journals abroad and the extent to which we seem to

00:35:58.920 --> 00:36:04.840
[Guest]: award prestige in return to journals abroad is a bit of an impediment and we need to find

00:36:04.840 --> 00:36:10.520
[Guest]: ways to create a deeply grounded local community, a domestic community that is here, that has

00:36:10.520 --> 00:36:16.880
[Guest]: an intuition into what are the questions and that chips away writing a literature on what

00:36:16.880 --> 00:36:21.560
[Guest]: is going on so that maybe we have a scientific and an analytical understanding and 20 human

00:36:21.560 --> 00:36:28.800
[Guest]: beings who embody that knowledge. The 20 human beings is as important as the 50 papers and

00:36:28.800 --> 00:36:35.520
[Guest]: blog articles that make up that knowledge. Then the next step is a creative process of

00:36:35.520 --> 00:36:43.160
[Guest]: inventing policy proposals. So there's a creative act of thinking that article 301 of the constitution

00:36:43.160 --> 00:36:49.480
[Guest]: is an opens up possibilities for a national market in agriculture and that it is possible

00:36:49.480 --> 00:36:56.380
[Guest]: for the union, for the parliament to legislate on this space. And this kind of creative thinking

00:36:56.380 --> 00:37:00.120
[Guest]: needs to take place and there need to be some people who will engage in this kind of creative

00:37:00.120 --> 00:37:04.920
[Guest]: thinking. For example, what I just said to you about contact tracing. Okay. It is a creative

00:37:04.920 --> 00:37:11.160
[Guest]: act of looking around this landscape and understanding that Arogya Setu is not an answer and that

00:37:11.160 --> 00:37:15.920
[Guest]: there is a complex public administration problem of how do you build contact tracing. And there

00:37:15.920 --> 00:37:22.440
[Guest]: is a real problem in this creative step because the academic journals do not publish such

00:37:22.440 --> 00:37:28.520
[Guest]: articles. So there is zero career incentive for anybody to do this kind of creativity

00:37:28.520 --> 00:37:33.280
[Guest]: to invent these things. So they come out as working papers and blog articles and they

00:37:33.280 --> 00:37:40.080
[Guest]: don't go into normal academic keeping score and getting jobs and getting promotions and

00:37:40.080 --> 00:37:46.640
[Guest]: so on. So that's a creative stage of inventing, competing, diverse policy proposals. And of

00:37:46.640 --> 00:37:52.480
[Guest]: course, many policy proposals tend to bubble out of the country itself. So industrialists

00:37:52.480 --> 00:38:00.080
[Guest]: and associations and various people, individuals, a person writing an opinion piece in a newspaper.

00:38:00.080 --> 00:38:04.720
[Guest]: Everybody dreams and comes up with creative proposals that why don't we solve this problem

00:38:04.720 --> 00:38:11.040
[Guest]: in X fashion. Then comes a great process of public debate where there are different rival

00:38:11.040 --> 00:38:15.640
[Guest]: solutions and they need to fight it out in the public domain, trying to persuade more

00:38:15.640 --> 00:38:20.320
[Guest]: people that, you know, this is the right idea and that is not the right idea. And in this,

00:38:20.320 --> 00:38:24.760
[Guest]: one of the more harmful things in India has been the extent to which incumbent government

00:38:24.760 --> 00:38:31.560
[Guest]: organizations have a disproportionate say in chilling this debate. So generally, if

00:38:31.560 --> 00:38:38.320
[Guest]: you are a reporter covering a beat, then you rely on access to the existing power structure

00:38:38.320 --> 00:38:43.000
[Guest]: and then it becomes impossible to write articles that question that power structure. So you

00:38:43.000 --> 00:38:48.600
[Guest]: get a whole bunch of newspaper stories that are supportive of the status quo. There's

00:38:48.600 --> 00:38:58.160
[Guest]: a very strong status quo bias in the conventional media system where it's difficult to express

00:38:58.160 --> 00:39:02.680
[Guest]: views that suggest that there's something going wrong with the mainstream government

00:39:02.680 --> 00:39:08.720
[Guest]: machinery. So we get a whole lot of praise in India. We get self praise that X agency

00:39:08.720 --> 00:39:12.600
[Guest]: has done a great job. You know, 90% of the coverage that you get is that X agency has

00:39:12.600 --> 00:39:17.200
[Guest]: done a great job. You don't actually get a good deal of critical thinking. There is a

00:39:17.200 --> 00:39:22.640
[Guest]: severe undersupply of criticism that we're not doing enough in terms of fostering that

00:39:22.640 --> 00:39:28.040
[Guest]: safety, that vibrant environment of criticism. Then the story turns to decision processes

00:39:28.040 --> 00:39:34.320
[Guest]: inside government. In my years in the Ministry of Finance, 2001 to 2005, it was an extremely

00:39:34.320 --> 00:39:40.560
[Guest]: intellectual environment where there would be these kinds of debates all the time where

00:39:40.560 --> 00:39:47.560
[Guest]: various papers and newspaper articles and opinion pieces and seminars and conferences

00:39:47.560 --> 00:39:51.600
[Guest]: would keep bubbling these debates and there would be a conversation going on in the Ministry

00:39:51.600 --> 00:39:57.960
[Guest]: of Finance all the time that should we be doing X or should we be doing Y. Similarly,

00:39:57.960 --> 00:40:01.560
[Guest]: there used to be a very simple accountability system. I have worked with three different

00:40:01.560 --> 00:40:05.680
[Guest]: finance ministers. I joined the Ministry of Finance when Yashwant Sinha was a minister.

00:40:05.680 --> 00:40:10.320
[Guest]: I stayed with Yashwant Singh. I stayed with P. J. Dambaram and I left in 2005. All the

00:40:10.320 --> 00:40:16.440
[Guest]: three ministers would take an opinion piece from a newspaper which is criticizing the

00:40:16.440 --> 00:40:21.920
[Guest]: government and send it down to the concerned officer and say, please speak. So the guy

00:40:21.920 --> 00:40:27.120
[Guest]: handling that portfolio would have to come back to the minister and justify himself or

00:40:27.120 --> 00:40:33.280
[Guest]: herself against the criticism that has come out in the newspaper. I thought that was absolutely

00:40:33.280 --> 00:40:40.080
[Guest]: fantastic. It was a way of bringing that external discourse inside the organization. Similarly,

00:40:40.080 --> 00:40:46.040
[Guest]: I remember Vijay Kelkar used to have a discipline in that period that he would read about 20

00:40:46.040 --> 00:40:50.000
[Guest]: opinion pieces in the newspapers every morning and he would pick two. And for two of those

00:40:50.000 --> 00:40:54.840
[Guest]: pieces, he would pick up the phone and talk to the author. So Kelkar knows everybody.

00:40:54.840 --> 00:40:59.040
[Guest]: So Kelkar would pick up the phone and talk to the authors and just go further. What were

00:40:59.040 --> 00:41:02.560
[Guest]: you thinking? What were you writing? What is your thinking on this adjacent problem

00:41:02.560 --> 00:41:06.240
[Guest]: and get a deeper sense. So for him, it was a very good investment that he would wake

00:41:06.240 --> 00:41:10.360
[Guest]: up in the morning, read all the opinion pieces of all the newspapers, follow up for one hour

00:41:10.360 --> 00:41:15.280
[Guest]: with two phone calls. And that's the way you keep the mind buzzing. It's important to listen

00:41:15.280 --> 00:41:20.240
[Guest]: to other people and particularly the people that don't agree, particularly the people

00:41:20.240 --> 00:41:25.160
[Guest]: that are criticizing the establishment, that are criticizing the government. And then in

00:41:25.160 --> 00:41:29.960
[Guest]: many important moments, the way the Indian public policy process works is that there

00:41:29.960 --> 00:41:36.720
[Guest]: is an expert committee. So it is easy to deride the expert committee process. And there is

00:41:36.720 --> 00:41:42.520
[Guest]: a lot of rubbish in the expert committee process. But as Ishar Aluwalia used to say, nothing

00:41:42.520 --> 00:41:48.120
[Guest]: ever got done by putting it in an expert committee report, but nothing ever got done without

00:41:48.120 --> 00:41:53.120
[Guest]: it being in 10 expert committee reports. So the expert committee process is a way of sifting

00:41:53.120 --> 00:41:59.320
[Guest]: through the landscape and, you know, keeping out the really kooky, nonsensical stuff and

00:41:59.320 --> 00:42:04.800
[Guest]: bringing about a judgment about what is the range of plausible alternatives of pretty

00:42:04.800 --> 00:42:11.440
[Guest]: much defining the Overton window, which then goes as the raw material to the real decision

00:42:11.440 --> 00:42:17.440
[Guest]: makers who are the politicians and the officials. And then some decisions get made and then

00:42:17.440 --> 00:42:22.200
[Guest]: some laws have to be drafted. That's a real weak link in India. There is, you know, very,

00:42:22.200 --> 00:42:27.560
[Guest]: very small number of people in India who have the expertise on how to draft laws correctly.

00:42:27.560 --> 00:42:32.920
[Guest]: Almost all law students in India don't know how to draft laws. And many, many laws get

00:42:32.920 --> 00:42:38.480
[Guest]: drafted reasonably badly. And finally, after a law is drafted, you need to create the public

00:42:38.480 --> 00:42:43.560
[Guest]: administration, the state capacity, the organizations that will enforce these laws in a reasonably

00:42:43.560 --> 00:42:49.360
[Guest]: effective way so that it doesn't just collapse into some authoritarian oppression where some

00:42:49.360 --> 00:42:55.960
[Guest]: officials hold arbitrary power over individuals. So this is the pipeline. Data, research, creative

00:42:55.960 --> 00:43:01.200
[Guest]: policy proposals, public debate, government, internal discussions, government committee

00:43:01.200 --> 00:43:07.040
[Guest]: process, government decisions, drafting of laws, building organizations that are the

00:43:07.040 --> 00:43:12.880
[Guest]: state capacity that enforce laws. This is the stylized track that we have to walk upon.

00:43:12.880 --> 00:43:19.120
[Guest]: A field works well when all these pieces work reasonably well. So in the 90s and the 2000s,

00:43:19.120 --> 00:43:25.160
[Guest]: we made progress in finance in India because there was a community of about 50 to 100 people

00:43:25.160 --> 00:43:30.720
[Guest]: who were the self-appointed owners of financial economic policy in India. And they were all

00:43:30.720 --> 00:43:37.840
[Guest]: over this process. So all the pieces of this pipeline were nurtured and built and stoked.

00:43:37.840 --> 00:43:44.200
[Guest]: And that is how we got a bunch of things done in that period. And a field which does not

00:43:44.200 --> 00:43:50.640
[Guest]: have this kind of community and which has appalling weaknesses in any one or two elements

00:43:50.640 --> 00:43:55.160
[Guest]: of the pipeline is a field where we flounder and fail.

00:43:55.160 --> 00:43:59.720
[Amit Varma]: And it strikes me, you know, you mentioned how something that is kooky and nonsensical,

00:43:59.720 --> 00:44:03.160
[Amit Varma]: you know, will not get through the expert committee process. And I immediately thought

00:44:03.160 --> 00:44:06.560
[Amit Varma]: of demonetization, which, of course, obviously went through no expert committee process.

00:44:06.560 --> 00:44:10.760
[Amit Varma]: Otherwise, it would never have survived. And equally, it seems to me that the farm bills

00:44:10.760 --> 00:44:15.840
[Amit Varma]: do seem to have come out of that kind of long process because these ideas have been put

00:44:15.840 --> 00:44:20.320
[Amit Varma]: forward and debated and discussed for donkey's years. In fact, these very proposals have

00:44:20.320 --> 00:44:24.760
[Amit Varma]: been on the manifestos of different political parties, like the Congress and the armed party

00:44:24.760 --> 00:44:30.000
[Amit Varma]: at different points in time. So would it then be correct to say that these reforms just

00:44:30.000 --> 00:44:34.480
[Amit Varma]: happen to have bubbled to the surface now and actually taken concrete shape, but they've

00:44:34.480 --> 00:44:37.080
[Amit Varma]: been more than a couple of decades in the making, right?

00:44:37.080 --> 00:44:45.200
[Guest]: In my opinion, the thoroughness of the upstream process that... So first, just so that everybody

00:44:45.200 --> 00:44:50.840
[Guest]: is clear where I stand. Fundamentally, I agree with the three farm bills. Okay. I have only

00:44:50.840 --> 00:44:54.560
[Guest]: small modifications that I would suggest to the farm bill. So just to put my biases on

00:44:54.560 --> 00:44:59.640
[Guest]: the table that I think that they are on the right track. 90%, 95%, they're on the right

00:44:59.640 --> 00:45:08.120
[Guest]: track. In my opinion, the process that led up to them was not sufficiently thorough.

00:45:08.120 --> 00:45:15.960
[Guest]: And there was an element of surprise and pushback that came because not enough had been done

00:45:15.960 --> 00:45:23.360
[Guest]: in terms of the public debate and the committee process and 200 seminars and conferences all

00:45:23.360 --> 00:45:28.520
[Guest]: over the country talking about these things, a draft law being out in public domain for

00:45:28.520 --> 00:45:32.920
[Guest]: several years, things like that. So I feel that the thoroughness of the process also

00:45:32.920 --> 00:45:36.760
[Guest]: helps in terms of the politics, because then there are no real surprises. You kind of know

00:45:36.760 --> 00:45:41.600
[Guest]: this is coming. It's been there for a long time. Several committee reports work on it.

00:45:41.600 --> 00:45:47.400
[Guest]: Each committee report triggers 100 events where there are seminars, conferences, podcast

00:45:47.400 --> 00:45:52.960
[Guest]: episodes, and so on, on every single important government committee report. And that's a

00:45:52.960 --> 00:45:57.000
[Guest]: part of how we get used to the idea. So I said the government committee process shapes

00:45:57.000 --> 00:46:01.320
[Guest]: the Overton window. And the surprise should happen in a government committee report, not

00:46:01.320 --> 00:46:07.800
[Guest]: in the doing. Because that's the point at which it's not as painful for a person that

00:46:07.800 --> 00:46:12.920
[Guest]: something comes out of the blue. So I think government committees are the right soft place

00:46:12.920 --> 00:46:18.560
[Guest]: that here's a new idea, which has been considered kooky all these years. And we are now legitimizing

00:46:18.560 --> 00:46:24.400
[Guest]: it. We are mainstreaming it. It's in the government committee process. So I have seen and I have

00:46:24.400 --> 00:46:31.480
[Guest]: written many documents which are inside the government file process. And it is almost

00:46:31.480 --> 00:46:36.920
[Guest]: mandatory for the file process to say inside the file that here's a problem. You need to

00:46:36.920 --> 00:46:40.560
[Guest]: demonstrate that it's a problem. Then you say, we've had these six committees which

00:46:40.560 --> 00:46:44.320
[Guest]: have written on this in the past. Then you put a quotation, quotation, quotation, quotation

00:46:44.320 --> 00:46:48.800
[Guest]: from six different government committees. So you say, look, we worked this to death.

00:46:48.800 --> 00:46:55.160
[Guest]: We've gone through the normal, thorough, systematic, hardworking government committee process. And

00:46:55.160 --> 00:46:59.600
[Guest]: there is a fair consensus between these diverse committees on what it is that is to be done.

00:46:59.600 --> 00:47:03.640
[Guest]: And so now we're ready to take the next step that it is time to draft a law. It is time

00:47:03.640 --> 00:47:11.080
[Guest]: to enact this law. So that catechism is the machinery of how a green sheet file ought

00:47:11.080 --> 00:47:15.600
[Guest]: to work. And the fact that it was out there in several committee reports, ideally a draft

00:47:15.600 --> 00:47:21.680
[Guest]: law was out there, helps to introduce the idea to everybody and reduce the surprise.

00:47:21.680 --> 00:47:28.520
[Guest]: And in my opinion, in the case of the three farm bills, which I agree with substantively,

00:47:28.520 --> 00:47:33.640
[Guest]: not enough was done in terms of these early stages of the pipeline. I think we've been

00:47:33.640 --> 00:47:40.320
[Guest]: cutting corners on the discussion and debate parts of the policy pipeline. The discussion

00:47:40.320 --> 00:47:44.680
[Guest]: and debate parts are partly valuable because discussion and debate improves the answer.

00:47:44.680 --> 00:47:49.120
[Guest]: They're also valuable in a political sense in that they sensitize the broader community

00:47:49.120 --> 00:47:50.120
[Guest]: for what is coming.

00:47:50.120 --> 00:47:54.840
[Amit Varma]: That's a great point. And we're going to take a short break after which we'll, you know,

00:47:54.840 --> 00:47:58.880
[Amit Varma]: just get down to the subject of agriculture and the reforms that you would like to see

00:47:58.880 --> 00:48:03.320
[Amit Varma]: happen and these farm bills and our historical problems and all of that. But before we go

00:48:03.320 --> 00:48:07.280
[Amit Varma]: to the break, sort of a quick question on the earlier subject of healthcare and the

00:48:07.280 --> 00:48:13.280
[Amit Varma]: pandemic that when you look at the government's approach towards the pandemic in India, and,

00:48:13.280 --> 00:48:16.680
[Amit Varma]: you know, right now it's not over, we still have to get a lot of the vaccination done

00:48:16.680 --> 00:48:21.320
[Amit Varma]: and all of those things to happen. What do you think are the faults in the framework

00:48:21.320 --> 00:48:25.800
[Amit Varma]: through which the government approaches this? Like one obvious fault that seems to me is

00:48:25.800 --> 00:48:29.760
[Amit Varma]: to have this sort of central planning conceit of the government will roll the vaccine out

00:48:29.760 --> 00:48:34.200
[Amit Varma]: and private participation is not really required, we'll control everything. Whereas I think

00:48:34.200 --> 00:48:38.440
[Amit Varma]: what instinctively strikes me as more reasonable is that yes, the government should put all

00:48:38.440 --> 00:48:42.240
[Amit Varma]: its effort in spreading everything out, but at the same time, allow the private sector

00:48:42.240 --> 00:48:47.320
[Amit Varma]: also to make it available, have multiple pipelines going. So, you know, if somebody wants to

00:48:47.320 --> 00:48:53.200
[Amit Varma]: pay a premium for it and sort of all that, that option should be kind of open to them.

00:48:53.200 --> 00:48:58.360
[Amit Varma]: So that seems to me to be one kind of point of dogma, which is getting in the way. But

00:48:58.360 --> 00:49:04.240
[Amit Varma]: broadly speaking, what are the top level two or three changes in attitude that you would

00:49:04.240 --> 00:49:05.240
[Amit Varma]: like to see?

00:49:05.240 --> 00:49:10.760
[Guest]: So the first I've already mentioned, which is prevention versus cure. I feel it is a

00:49:10.760 --> 00:49:16.720
[Guest]: moral imperative and it is the sane, rational thing to do to really put a high focus on

00:49:16.720 --> 00:49:22.440
[Guest]: prevention. And when you pause to think about what shapes prevention, it's a fundamental

00:49:22.440 --> 00:49:28.520
[Guest]: fact that most of it is not the work of doctors, is not the work of Ministry of Health. So

00:49:28.520 --> 00:49:36.600
[Guest]: as an example, the giant health crises of India are owing to air quality, owing to water

00:49:36.600 --> 00:49:41.600
[Guest]: and sanitation, owing to road safety. Okay. These kinds of things are sitting outside

00:49:41.600 --> 00:49:47.640
[Guest]: a Ministry of Health. Consider a problem like natural disasters. We in India are building

00:49:47.640 --> 00:49:54.040
[Guest]: an urban environment, which is extremely unsafe and is ready for floods and earthquakes to

00:49:54.040 --> 00:50:00.640
[Guest]: generate devastating consequences for the health and the lives of people. So you need

00:50:00.640 --> 00:50:07.080
[Guest]: to go after disaster risk resilience, which is not seen as a Ministry of Health activity.

00:50:07.080 --> 00:50:12.120
[Guest]: Consider the food system, that how to increase the nutritive quality of food, how to reduce

00:50:12.120 --> 00:50:19.120
[Guest]: the role of wheat and rice in our diet. This is food system transformation. And again,

00:50:19.120 --> 00:50:24.680
[Guest]: it is not inside the Ministry of Health. So conceptually, I feel that if you take prevention

00:50:24.680 --> 00:50:31.080
[Guest]: seriously, then there is a cross-cutting health agenda that influences many, many elements

00:50:31.080 --> 00:50:37.880
[Guest]: of government. It is a Ministry of Environment and Agriculture that will impact on air quality.

00:50:37.880 --> 00:50:44.320
[Guest]: It is a Ministry of Agriculture that will reshape the food system. It is the Ministry

00:50:44.320 --> 00:50:51.800
[Guest]: of Roads that will build better road safety. It is the water and the sanitation crew that

00:50:51.800 --> 00:50:57.040
[Guest]: will improve the water system. It is a whole complicated problem about urban planning and

00:50:57.040 --> 00:51:02.840
[Guest]: the built environment that will generate disaster risk resilience and so on. So it seems to

00:51:02.840 --> 00:51:10.600
[Guest]: me that we need a new kind of collaboration muscle where we are able to bring an across-the-government

00:51:10.600 --> 00:51:18.840
[Guest]: approach to putting health policy into the working of many, many ministries. And to continue

00:51:18.840 --> 00:51:23.520
[Guest]: on where we were a moment ago, as you know, I work in many, many fields, but I have been

00:51:23.520 --> 00:51:28.640
[Guest]: reasonably worried about the quality and the capabilities of the health policy community

00:51:28.640 --> 00:51:32.960
[Guest]: in India. We really don't have a community that is commensurate with the problems of

00:51:32.960 --> 00:51:38.440
[Guest]: health policy. So it's not entirely accidental that health policy is one of the weakest areas

00:51:38.440 --> 00:51:44.040
[Guest]: in India in terms of what the Indian state is doing. And it has to do with the kind of

00:51:44.040 --> 00:51:49.320
[Guest]: capabilities of this community. It also has to do with the domination of doctors. So just

00:51:49.320 --> 00:51:55.680
[Guest]: because a person is a great doctor and is definitely my go-to person when I get tuberculosis,

00:51:55.680 --> 00:51:59.680
[Guest]: that doesn't mean that this person is the right person to think about health policy,

00:51:59.680 --> 00:52:06.320
[Guest]: to think about public health. That's a different capability altogether. And we have just not

00:52:06.320 --> 00:52:14.080
[Guest]: succeeded in laying the foundations of those 50 key people of the right data sets of the

00:52:14.080 --> 00:52:15.080
[Guest]: researchers.

00:52:15.080 --> 00:52:21.560
[Guest]: So on the research side, we don't get much useful health in terms of the research papers

00:52:21.560 --> 00:52:28.000
[Guest]: that are written because partly a lot of the economists are pursuing the overseas development

00:52:28.000 --> 00:52:34.000
[Guest]: economics journals who are really fundamentally cut off from India, public administration,

00:52:34.000 --> 00:52:39.880
[Guest]: public policy. And I mean, there is a game of publishing in those journals that is rather

00:52:39.880 --> 00:52:45.680
[Guest]: lacking in its ability to illuminate the problems of public policy in India where the rubber

00:52:45.680 --> 00:52:46.680
[Guest]: hits the road.

00:52:46.680 --> 00:52:51.600
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. And it seems to me to be a sort of a problem of like you need a community of problem

00:52:51.600 --> 00:52:55.820
[Amit Varma]: solvers, which would include economists. But then you look at the incentives for economists

00:52:55.820 --> 00:53:00.960
[Amit Varma]: for many of these, it is to become part of this whole circus of, you know, publishing

00:53:00.960 --> 00:53:06.040
[Amit Varma]: in journals abroad and rising up the academic ladder there and so on and so forth. And,

00:53:06.040 --> 00:53:12.040
[Amit Varma]: you know, what can kind of change that? Because what we don't really see so much of is economists

00:53:12.040 --> 00:53:16.640
[Amit Varma]: here really aspiring to be public intellectuals and hoping to make change. What are the incentives

00:53:16.640 --> 00:53:22.440
[Amit Varma]: for those who ignore that particular sort of path and choose to sort of make a change

00:53:22.440 --> 00:53:26.400
[Amit Varma]: here? Like you came back to India at one point and you kind of gave up that path and you

00:53:26.400 --> 00:53:31.120
[Amit Varma]: came back to this path. And we've, of course, discussed this in a past episode. But briefly,

00:53:31.120 --> 00:53:35.040
[Amit Varma]: you know, is that something that worries you that too many people who could make a difference

00:53:35.040 --> 00:53:40.040
[Amit Varma]: drift away because their incentives are different? And therefore, there is a lack of intellectual

00:53:40.040 --> 00:53:42.360
[Amit Varma]: capacity working on these problems?

00:53:42.360 --> 00:53:50.880
[Guest]: There is a real incentives problem. So health policy is currently designed by doctors and

00:53:50.880 --> 00:53:56.080
[Guest]: it is healthcare focused and it tends to think that there is a government and the government

00:53:56.080 --> 00:54:00.640
[Guest]: is like one big PSU. They own a lot of hospitals and they want to run those hospitals. And

00:54:00.640 --> 00:54:06.040
[Guest]: there's really very little health policy going beyond that. Governments tend to think that

00:54:06.040 --> 00:54:11.160
[Guest]: the health is the job of the Ministry of Health. So, you know, we're stuck because a Ministry

00:54:11.160 --> 00:54:16.520
[Guest]: of Health tends to be doctor dominated. You may have heard me often say that one of the

00:54:16.520 --> 00:54:23.240
[Guest]: least effective pathways to thinking about public policy in India is to ask an IIT engineer

00:54:23.240 --> 00:54:27.040
[Guest]: how to solve the problem. Well, in similar fashion, one of the least effective ways to

00:54:27.040 --> 00:54:32.840
[Guest]: find solutions in health policy is to ask a doctor how to make progress on health policy.

00:54:32.840 --> 00:54:39.520
[Guest]: And one pathway to change things would have been intellectual leadership at the level

00:54:39.520 --> 00:54:45.040
[Guest]: of a Ministry of Finance and a Prime Minister, which who are able to see things in a more

00:54:45.040 --> 00:54:49.360
[Guest]: intellectual way and look at the world in a different way compared to how a Ministry

00:54:49.360 --> 00:54:54.840
[Guest]: of Health sees it. Another element of the change will be philanthropy and philanthropic

00:54:54.840 --> 00:55:02.760
[Guest]: capital. In my opinion, so far, the impact and usefulness of philanthropy in India has

00:55:02.760 --> 00:55:07.800
[Guest]: been limited, partly because most philanthropy tends to think about running programs and

00:55:07.800 --> 00:55:15.840
[Guest]: not thinking about policy. So people get satisfied when they give lunches to 1000 kids, but not

00:55:15.840 --> 00:55:20.240
[Guest]: in getting research done and getting the landscape of ideas to change. So I think that there's

00:55:20.240 --> 00:55:25.960
[Guest]: a very basic kind of philanthropy that tends to rule the roost, which is nice. It makes

00:55:25.960 --> 00:55:33.120
[Guest]: you feel good. But frankly, it is one upon 1000 of the impact that can be obtained by

00:55:33.120 --> 00:55:37.360
[Guest]: changing the landscape of ideas and by changing the way we think about these things. Another

00:55:37.360 --> 00:55:43.080
[Guest]: problem is that a lot of philanthropists build organizations and the employees of those organizations

00:55:43.080 --> 00:55:50.000
[Guest]: crave government engagement. They are judged by their ability to influence public policy

00:55:50.000 --> 00:55:55.240
[Guest]: on a day-to-day basis in the extent to which they are friends with joint secretaries and

00:55:55.240 --> 00:56:03.000
[Guest]: secretaries of government. And in the extreme, many of philanthropy in India is an extended

00:56:03.000 --> 00:56:10.040
[Guest]: arm of the Indian state, because the Indian state gets a very large say on how the philanthropic

00:56:10.040 --> 00:56:15.040
[Guest]: capital is being deployed and allocated. And in my opinion, that's a shame because it could

00:56:15.040 --> 00:56:16.200
[Guest]: be done so much better.

00:56:16.200 --> 00:56:21.120
[Amit Varma]: No, it is a shame. In fact, in the last episode I did with Ruben Mascarenas, he was talking

00:56:21.120 --> 00:56:25.940
[Amit Varma]: about how when they reached out to companies for the CSR funds, they were told by companies

00:56:25.940 --> 00:56:30.640
[Amit Varma]: that they had all been told to give the CSR funds to the PMKs fund, which, of course,

00:56:30.640 --> 00:56:37.960
[Amit Varma]: is an astronomical black hole, which is a bit of a pity. But you know, lots to unpack

00:56:37.960 --> 00:56:41.800
[Amit Varma]: here and maybe one day we can do a separate episode on all of this because it seems really

00:56:41.800 --> 00:56:45.760
[Amit Varma]: fascinating. But for the moment, let's take a quick commercial break and then we can start

