[Amit Varma]: so on and so forth. You know, I've had episodes on why there are no futures markets and, you

00:58:33.080 --> 00:58:37.920
[Amit Varma]: know, how because there is no corporatization, there's no chance for scale. Farmers are forced

00:58:37.920 --> 00:58:43.680
[Amit Varma]: to be entrepreneurs besides their core competency of farming, which is really unfair. It's just

00:58:43.680 --> 00:58:48.520
[Amit Varma]: an entire kind of litany of things. Now, in your recent writing, including articles that

00:58:48.520 --> 00:58:54.560
[Amit Varma]: are linked from the show notes, you've kind of narrowed down a few basic areas in which,

00:58:54.560 --> 00:58:58.960
[Amit Varma]: you know, you think that we can reform immediately and the farm bills tackle one of them, but

00:58:58.960 --> 00:59:04.560
[Amit Varma]: not all of them. So kind of take me through your thinking of this from, you know, starting

00:59:04.560 --> 00:59:08.880
[Amit Varma]: again at the meta level from the first principles of what is wrong and then how those can be

00:59:08.880 --> 00:59:11.360
[Amit Varma]: fixed and what the benefit to us will be.

00:59:11.360 --> 00:59:18.080
[Guest]: So it's very useful to think about the decisions that are made in the path to the production

00:59:18.080 --> 00:59:23.360
[Guest]: of food. Okay, so economics is about decisions. And so the first question we should ask is,

00:59:23.360 --> 00:59:28.360
[Guest]: what are the decisions? And there are actually exactly three decisions that are made in the

00:59:28.360 --> 00:59:33.600
[Guest]: field of agriculture. The first decision is what to sow. Okay, so you have some land and

00:59:33.600 --> 00:59:37.680
[Guest]: do you put wheat or do you put rice or do you put potatoes or whatever? It's the first

00:59:37.680 --> 00:59:41.960
[Guest]: decision. So it's a very important decision. And we need to think about how that decision

00:59:41.960 --> 00:59:50.400
[Guest]: happens. The second decision is how much money to spend on putting inputs into the period

00:59:50.400 --> 00:59:55.600
[Guest]: in which the crops are growing. So how much money do you put for fertilizers, for high

00:59:55.600 --> 01:00:02.600
[Guest]: yielding varieties and so on, purchase of water. And the third decision is that of storage,

01:00:02.600 --> 01:00:08.520
[Guest]: that some economic agents in the country choose to store goods. It could be that the farmer

01:00:08.520 --> 01:00:14.160
[Guest]: has some kutcha storage right there where he has harvested the crop, or it could be

01:00:14.160 --> 01:00:20.440
[Guest]: a more professional environment where somebody else buys goods on the spot market, puts them

01:00:20.440 --> 01:00:25.720
[Guest]: in a warehouse and carries them into a future date. Okay, so that's how we transport agricultural

01:00:25.720 --> 01:00:31.280
[Guest]: goods through time. We put them into storage. These are the three fundamental decisions

01:00:31.280 --> 01:00:38.000
[Guest]: that are made. What to sow, how much to put as inputs and what to store, when to store.

01:00:38.000 --> 01:00:44.840
[Guest]: So we should think of all the factors that influence and shape these decisions. How can

01:00:44.840 --> 01:00:50.280
[Guest]: you create a good environment where rational thinking individuals make better decisions

01:00:50.280 --> 01:00:55.760
[Guest]: on what to sow? How can you create a better environment where inputs are chosen in a rational

01:00:55.760 --> 01:01:01.480
[Guest]: way that generates the correct outcomes? And how can you produce more rational decisions

01:01:01.480 --> 01:01:07.760
[Guest]: about storage? This is a nice x-ray that helps you to understand what is going wrong in agriculture.

01:01:07.760 --> 01:01:13.480
[Guest]: So everything that is going wrong in agriculture is about state-induced distortions in these

01:01:13.480 --> 01:01:18.720
[Guest]: three decisions, that the government is messing with the decision of what to sow, is messing

01:01:18.720 --> 01:01:25.480
[Guest]: with the inputs decision, is messing with the storage decision. And these three classes

01:01:25.480 --> 01:01:32.960
[Guest]: of difficulties are coming together and generating a bad life for the agriculturists of India.

01:01:32.960 --> 01:01:37.960
[Guest]: That's a useful, simple way to think about the whole thing.

01:01:37.960 --> 01:01:41.280
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, let's, for example, talk about the decision of what to sow. Now, typically,

01:01:41.280 --> 01:01:45.640
[Amit Varma]: what happens is if you look at a marketplace where there is demand and there is supply,

01:01:45.640 --> 01:01:49.120
[Amit Varma]: how would an agriculturalist decide what to sow? He would do it on the basis of prices.

01:01:49.120 --> 01:01:54.320
[Amit Varma]: Like the best way for you to get information about what do people need, what do people

01:01:54.320 --> 01:01:59.040
[Amit Varma]: value is to look at the prices and say that, okay, from the prices it appears that there

01:01:59.040 --> 01:02:04.080
[Amit Varma]: is a shortage in this particular thing, in commodity X, and therefore, I will sow more

01:02:04.080 --> 01:02:09.000
[Amit Varma]: of commodity X and fulfil that. And obviously, this also leads to what Paul Samuelson called

01:02:09.000 --> 01:02:14.440
[Amit Varma]: the cobweb effect, which I'll come to later. But broadly, this is how prices would determine

01:02:14.440 --> 01:02:20.400
[Amit Varma]: – and this is how prices determine everything elsewhere. Like, you know, my entire housing

01:02:20.400 --> 01:02:24.400
[Amit Varma]: society feeds itself every morning, not because some central planner sits there and in all

01:02:24.400 --> 01:02:29.360
[Amit Varma]: his wisdom decides what each person will want. But because, you know, we have our routines

01:02:29.360 --> 01:02:33.680
[Amit Varma]: of what we buy and all of that, and they affect the prices every day. And similarly, producers

01:02:33.680 --> 01:02:38.240
[Amit Varma]: produce according to that and all of that. One doesn't, I think, really need to describe

01:02:38.240 --> 01:02:42.400
[Amit Varma]: the price system in that way. Now, the distortion comes in when the government says that, look,

01:02:42.400 --> 01:02:48.400
[Amit Varma]: I'll give you, for example, like, I'll give you an MSP for, you know, produce Y. And at

01:02:48.400 --> 01:02:51.920
[Amit Varma]: which point in time that distorts the signal that is coming from the marketplace, because

01:02:51.920 --> 01:02:57.320
[Amit Varma]: now the farmer is incentivized to make produce Y because he's got a guaranteed MSP income

01:02:57.320 --> 01:03:02.760
[Amit Varma]: at the end of it, and therefore ignore produce X, which is what the people might also want.

01:03:02.760 --> 01:03:08.240
[Amit Varma]: And where this can get particularly sort of pernicious is when, for example, Punjab's

01:03:08.240 --> 01:03:13.280
[Amit Varma]: involvement with rice. Number one, there is, of course, you know, they have these MSP incentives

01:03:13.280 --> 01:03:19.400
[Amit Varma]: to make rice and sell rice. Number two, you know, rice is a water intensive product. Punjab

01:03:19.400 --> 01:03:22.960
[Amit Varma]: is slightly on the arid side, they should not be making rice to begin with. But they

01:03:22.960 --> 01:03:28.240
[Amit Varma]: do that because you introduced another distortion by giving them free electricity to farmers.

01:03:28.240 --> 01:03:33.240
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, they can, you know, dig bore wells and draw out plenty of groundwater to

01:03:33.240 --> 01:03:38.680
[Amit Varma]: grow rice with, which leads to a water problem. And I've also had episodes on the water problems

01:03:38.680 --> 01:03:44.160
[Amit Varma]: that this leads to. So you have all of these different distortions. And one of the unintended

01:03:44.160 --> 01:03:48.720
[Amit Varma]: consequences or unseen effects of all of this of Punjabi farmers growing rice is the air

01:03:48.720 --> 01:03:54.080
[Amit Varma]: pollution in Delhi, for example, because then they burn the stubble and the winds carry

01:03:54.080 --> 01:03:58.880
[Amit Varma]: it to Delhi and the air pollution there is exacerbated. And you're like, how do we even

01:03:58.880 --> 01:04:03.800
[Amit Varma]: solve this massive problem? And as you pointed out earlier, air quality is a public health

01:04:03.800 --> 01:04:09.960
[Amit Varma]: issue. So is it then the case that one of the fundamental distortions which really messes

01:04:09.960 --> 01:04:15.120
[Amit Varma]: all of this up is sort of MSPs, which are by the way, not the subject of the farm bills,

01:04:15.120 --> 01:04:18.960
[Amit Varma]: you know, in spite of what so many people seem to think. The farm bills, I don't think

01:04:18.960 --> 01:04:26.440
[Amit Varma]: mention MSPs at all. But, you know, is this a fundamental sort of distortion when it comes

01:04:26.440 --> 01:04:29.080
[Amit Varma]: to that first question you raised on what to sow?

01:04:29.080 --> 01:04:34.800
[Guest]: MSP is indeed a fundamental distortion. The impact of MSP upon the economy is smaller

01:04:34.800 --> 01:04:39.640
[Guest]: than meets the eye, because for a large number of crops at a large number of locations in

01:04:39.640 --> 01:04:45.680
[Guest]: India, the administrative machinery for implementing MSP is not there. So actually the damage that

01:04:45.680 --> 01:04:50.440
[Guest]: MSP is doing to India is smaller than meets the eye. So for many people, MSP looms large.

01:04:50.440 --> 01:04:54.880
[Guest]: It's actually not as big a problem as it is made out to be. As you correctly said, there

01:04:54.880 --> 01:05:01.360
[Guest]: is not a hint of MSP in these farm bills. And we'll come to that when we talk more about

01:05:01.360 --> 01:05:06.880
[Guest]: the problem of national market. Equally important in the price question, in my opinion, is the

01:05:06.880 --> 01:05:12.160
[Guest]: problem of the futures markets. That when in June I'm making a decision on what to do

01:05:12.160 --> 01:05:18.040
[Guest]: with my Kharif land, I need to make decisions based on my expectations about what the price

01:05:18.040 --> 01:05:24.480
[Guest]: will be in October. And there is no clarity on what the price will be in October. And

01:05:24.480 --> 01:05:30.400
[Guest]: the solution basically is once again to use prices as the information system. The price

01:05:30.400 --> 01:05:36.000
[Guest]: in October is visible in the futures market. Some people may choose to actually lock in

01:05:36.000 --> 01:05:41.880
[Guest]: a sale price using a futures market, but that's just a tiny tip of the iceberg. 99% of the

01:05:41.880 --> 01:05:47.000
[Guest]: people just benefit, get a positive externality because they're able to see the price on the

01:05:47.000 --> 01:05:51.480
[Guest]: futures market. It gives you the best available estimate. It's not a guarantee unless you

01:05:51.480 --> 01:05:55.520
[Guest]: choose to lock in. So it is available as a guarantee if you choose to lock in. If you

01:05:55.520 --> 01:06:00.280
[Guest]: choose to not lock in, it's not a guarantee, but it's the best available estimator for

01:06:00.280 --> 01:06:06.560
[Guest]: what will be prevailing conditions in October. So putting together supply, demand, global

01:06:06.560 --> 01:06:13.080
[Guest]: conditions, everything, the futures price is what people can use as an information system

01:06:13.080 --> 01:06:17.400
[Guest]: to make better decisions about what to sell. And one of the many things that the Indian

01:06:17.400 --> 01:06:23.680
[Guest]: state does is to damage the ability to get to a sensible commodity futures market.

01:06:23.680 --> 01:06:27.840
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, demystify this for me. And like, of course I agree with you, but most people

01:06:27.840 --> 01:06:31.640
[Amit Varma]: listening to this will be like, you know, futures market sounds like something that

01:06:31.640 --> 01:06:36.400
[Amit Varma]: is very sophisticated, which investors with computers and Bloomberg terminals will sit

01:06:36.400 --> 01:06:40.560
[Amit Varma]: down and look at. And I've done an episode where I've kind of demystified this ages ago.

01:06:40.560 --> 01:06:45.800
[Amit Varma]: I think it was a short 15 minute episode with Karthik Shashidhar, but sort of demystify

01:06:45.800 --> 01:06:48.880
[Amit Varma]: this for me. How does it help the practical farmer on the ground? Like, let's say I'm

01:06:48.880 --> 01:06:53.120
[Amit Varma]: a farmer and I'm deciding what to sow and I'm making my decisions for the next season

01:06:53.120 --> 01:06:59.680
[Amit Varma]: ki yeh banana hai, itna invest karna hai. How do futures markets help me in those practical

01:06:59.680 --> 01:07:01.960
[Guest]: terms?

01:07:01.960 --> 01:07:07.960
[Guest]: So what is the spot market? There is a market where people are buying and selling cotton

01:07:07.960 --> 01:07:12.600
[Guest]: for delivery just now. So on the spot, I'll pay you money, you'll give me the cotton.

01:07:12.600 --> 01:07:18.600
[Guest]: What is the futures market? It's where you and I agree on a transaction today, but the

01:07:18.600 --> 01:07:22.560
[Guest]: money and the cotton will be exchanged six months out. Okay, that's it. Nothing else

01:07:22.560 --> 01:07:27.560
[Guest]: is different. It is exactly the same as doing a transaction, except so we lock in on the

01:07:27.560 --> 01:07:32.800
[Guest]: price and quantity, but the actual transaction will be consummated six months from now. Six

01:07:32.800 --> 01:07:37.200
[Guest]: months from now, you'll give me the money and I'll give you the cotton. Okay. So there

01:07:37.200 --> 01:07:40.760
[Guest]: is a price that is visible in that market because there are many, many people participating

01:07:40.760 --> 01:07:41.760
[Guest]: in it.

01:07:41.760 --> 01:07:45.800
[Guest]: And that brings me to the decision of what to sow. Imagine that there's a person who's

01:07:45.800 --> 01:07:51.360
[Guest]: making a decision about whether I should be sowing tur dal or I should be sowing cotton.

01:07:51.360 --> 01:07:58.280
[Guest]: Okay. So I'm signing in June and I'm making the decision about what to sow. And I make

01:07:58.280 --> 01:08:03.360
[Guest]: my calculations that I will spend so much money on fertilizer and so much money on buying

01:08:03.360 --> 01:08:09.560
[Guest]: the seeds and so on. And what will be my prospective revenue when the goods come out? Answer is

01:08:09.560 --> 01:08:13.720
[Guest]: I just glance at the futures price. That's all. It's very simple. It's not complicated.

01:08:13.720 --> 01:08:18.040
[Guest]: All over the world, farmers do that. It's not an unreasonable ask that instead of taking

01:08:18.040 --> 01:08:24.560
[Guest]: today's spot price of cotton, take the spot price on the date at which your harvest will

01:08:24.560 --> 01:08:29.640
[Guest]: be out and you will be selling into the market. It's a very simple and reasonable ask. Okay.

01:08:29.640 --> 01:08:38.520
[Guest]: And case two, you may decide that I am so risk averse that I want to remove the risk

01:08:38.520 --> 01:08:42.920
[Guest]: that I have about the future price. No problem. Go to the futures market, sell your goods

01:08:42.920 --> 01:08:47.440
[Guest]: there. So you've got a locked in price. So these are the choices. At case one, you just

01:08:47.440 --> 01:08:50.800
[Guest]: look at the price and you say, look, the price will fluctuate. But standing today, this is

01:08:50.800 --> 01:08:55.040
[Guest]: my best estimator. Case two, you say, no, you know, I'm totally risk averse. I don't

01:08:55.040 --> 01:08:59.600
[Guest]: want to take any chances. I want to sell my goods today at that locked in price. Sure,

01:08:59.600 --> 01:09:04.800
[Guest]: do that. It's called the futures market. So this is the magic of the futures market. And

01:09:04.800 --> 01:09:10.120
[Guest]: it is really a very, very important element of any healthy agricultural system.

01:09:10.120 --> 01:09:14.760
[Amit Varma]: No, and it does sound magical to me because, you know, if there's a spot market, I can

01:09:14.760 --> 01:09:18.280
[Amit Varma]: plan only for today. I know what the price is today. I have no way of figuring out what

01:09:18.280 --> 01:09:22.800
[Amit Varma]: the price will be six months from now. Whereas the futures market will give the agriculturalist

01:09:22.800 --> 01:09:28.040
[Amit Varma]: that level of comfort that, okay, I can plan now. So it is almost like an MSP, except that

01:09:28.040 --> 01:09:32.320
[Amit Varma]: it is not given by the government. There is no element of coercion. And it is also not

01:09:32.320 --> 01:09:36.480
[Amit Varma]: giving him a wrong signal like a government MSP would give. Instead, it is a market which

01:09:36.480 --> 01:09:43.220
[Amit Varma]: is determining future prices. And therefore, those signals are sort of that much more accurate.

01:09:43.220 --> 01:09:45.720
[Amit Varma]: So why are they not allowed? Is it because of this sort of ideological?

01:09:45.720 --> 01:09:52.480
[Guest]: They are not allowed, but it's a part of the broader failure on financial markets in India,

01:09:52.480 --> 01:09:58.880
[Guest]: that there is a whole array of restrictions, which has damaged the ability of these markets

01:09:58.880 --> 01:10:03.080
[Guest]: to do their work. So the markets are actually minuscule and the price discovery is not so

01:10:03.080 --> 01:10:09.320
[Guest]: great. And it doesn't work in the way that it is intended to work.

01:10:09.320 --> 01:10:13.320
[Amit Varma]: And another sort of point that you've made is that, you know, right now, there are no

01:10:13.320 --> 01:10:17.960
[Amit Varma]: sources of stability. Farmers are, of course, forced to also be entrepreneurs. They want

01:10:17.960 --> 01:10:23.380
[Amit Varma]: stability and it seems to them that the handout of an MSP is, you know, some kind of stability.

01:10:23.380 --> 01:10:27.360
[Amit Varma]: They have some basis on which to plan. But as you've pointed out, that international

01:10:27.360 --> 01:10:31.360
[Amit Varma]: trade is a much better source of that, because if your minimum price is going to be the market

01:10:31.360 --> 01:10:36.360
[Amit Varma]: price that the world is offering, then that is a better MSP than an MSP that the government

01:10:36.360 --> 01:10:41.560
[Amit Varma]: can offer. You know, it gives you the same sense of security. It gives you a much broader

01:10:41.560 --> 01:10:46.960
[Amit Varma]: market and therefore better prices for your goods. And obviously, you will only be selling

01:10:46.960 --> 01:10:51.160
[Amit Varma]: things there when there is a glut of supply here. So instead of things getting wasted,

01:10:51.160 --> 01:10:55.720
[Amit Varma]: you actually have a kind of market for it there. So what is the thought of thinking

01:10:55.720 --> 01:11:00.920
[Amit Varma]: on this? Because what one gets to hear from the policy landscape, if like me, you're just

01:11:00.920 --> 01:11:04.760
[Amit Varma]: a casual observer and you just peruse the papers once in a while, and once in a while,

01:11:04.760 --> 01:11:08.840
[Amit Varma]: you'll see some news about, oh, you know, onion exports have been banned now and oh,

01:11:08.840 --> 01:11:13.360
[Amit Varma]: onion exports are back. And it seems to me extremely unpredictable and chaotic and even

01:11:13.360 --> 01:11:19.000
[Amit Varma]: moody if one may use that term for the state, where there's no predictability, you know,

01:11:19.000 --> 01:11:25.160
[Amit Varma]: farmers can't plan for an export policy and look ahead. And so according to that and equally,

01:11:25.160 --> 01:11:29.760
[Amit Varma]: you know, people who might buy our stuff from abroad can't also make long term plans because

01:11:29.760 --> 01:11:36.320
[Guest]: everything is so arbit. So in the thinking about international trade, yes, international

01:11:36.320 --> 01:11:41.120
[Guest]: trade is a tremendous source of stability, that when there is a harvest in India, which

01:11:41.120 --> 01:11:46.200
[Guest]: is a glut, you want to put things on ships and planes and send them out. Okay. And vice

01:11:46.200 --> 01:11:50.400
[Guest]: versa, when there's a shortage in India, we want to be able to readily import things from

01:11:50.400 --> 01:11:55.840
[Guest]: abroad. In this one very important thing to remember is that we should not think about

01:11:55.840 --> 01:12:01.600
[Guest]: the word India will import wheat or India will import cotton, because then that tends

01:12:01.600 --> 01:12:06.840
[Guest]: to equate it with the Indian state. Okay, actually, all that we need is for the government

01:12:06.840 --> 01:12:10.400
[Guest]: to get out of the way, then private people will do everything. So then private people

01:12:10.400 --> 01:12:15.280
[Guest]: have all the right incentives, that private people will be watching the price in Singapore

01:12:15.280 --> 01:12:21.560
[Guest]: or in Dubai, and will buy in Singapore, sell in India, buy in India, sell in Singapore,

01:12:21.560 --> 01:12:28.080
[Guest]: figure out that, you know, I could actually put tomatoes into planes and ship them out

01:12:28.080 --> 01:12:33.840
[Guest]: to Dubai and that I'm able to generate a good profit. So a large number of practical decisions

01:12:33.840 --> 01:12:40.600
[Guest]: made by one individual firm, one individual trader at a time, is the right vision that

01:12:40.600 --> 01:12:44.440
[Guest]: we should be having. We should not think of the word India, because it completely messes

01:12:44.440 --> 01:12:48.960
[Guest]: with our brain. So we start thinking that India will demand 10 million tons of wheat

01:12:48.960 --> 01:12:52.600
[Guest]: and the world market may not provide it. Okay. So first of all, there is no, there should

01:12:52.600 --> 01:12:58.360
[Guest]: not be an India, a single national body. There should be large numbers of individual decisions

01:12:58.360 --> 01:13:02.800
[Guest]: and many, many, many decisions will get made. Some people will choose to hold inventory

01:13:02.800 --> 01:13:06.960
[Guest]: in India. Some people will look at the futures market. They will say, Hey, I think there's

01:13:06.960 --> 01:13:11.920
[Guest]: a big increase in the price of wheat that is going to happen in the next few months.

01:13:11.920 --> 01:13:16.520
[Guest]: Let me import wheat right now and let me store it in India so that I'm ready to sell into

01:13:16.520 --> 01:13:21.400
[Guest]: the Indian market day by day, week by week. As the price unfolds, there are big industrial

01:13:21.400 --> 01:13:29.240
[Guest]: buyers like ITC, which makes Atta or Britannia, which makes bread and biscuits. They will

01:13:29.240 --> 01:13:34.600
[Guest]: constantly have that intelligence of sourcing wheat all over the world, making rational

01:13:34.600 --> 01:13:41.320
[Guest]: decisions about when to store, how much to store. And these hundreds of equilibrating

01:13:41.320 --> 01:13:47.000
[Guest]: decisions will bring about more stability in the Indian market. So we should think of

01:13:47.000 --> 01:13:53.760
[Guest]: the international market as a giant buffer, which protects the Indian market from fluctuations

01:13:53.760 --> 01:13:58.880
[Guest]: that either consumers or producers get affected because of the crazy volatility of Indian

01:13:58.880 --> 01:14:07.440
[Guest]: prices. And the solution to that is to have a very open environment on international trade.

01:14:07.440 --> 01:14:11.920
[Amit Varma]: One of the pieces which you sent me, which I enjoyed reading, has a headline, an agricultural

01:14:11.920 --> 01:14:17.320
[Amit Varma]: trade powerhouse, which I'll link from the show notes. And there you make the very interesting

01:14:17.320 --> 01:14:21.400
[Amit Varma]: point that, as the headline says, that we can be an agricultural trade powerhouse. And

01:14:21.400 --> 01:14:25.360
[Amit Varma]: typically I think a lot of Indians, when they think about the economy, think about how,

01:14:25.360 --> 01:14:28.960
[Amit Varma]: you know, we are doing well in services now, almost by default that happened post liberalization

01:14:28.960 --> 01:14:33.480
[Amit Varma]: wasn't regulated. But we missed the bus when it came to labor intensive manufacture, where

01:14:33.480 --> 01:14:37.920
[Amit Varma]: because we have so much cheap labor, we could actually like China and maybe in the later

01:14:37.920 --> 01:14:42.760
[Amit Varma]: day like Vietnam and so on. And like Bangladesh is also doing so well in it. And we missed

01:14:42.760 --> 01:14:46.600
[Amit Varma]: that bus completely. And maybe we'll never catch it because of automation. But people

01:14:46.600 --> 01:14:54.040
[Amit Varma]: often don't think about agriculture as a big source of economic growth. And you point out

01:14:54.040 --> 01:14:58.920
[Amit Varma]: at one point, and I'll quote from your piece, quote, what many of us have not noticed is

01:14:58.920 --> 01:15:04.200
[Amit Varma]: that a labor intensive industry agriculture now yields greater exports than automobiles

01:15:04.200 --> 01:15:09.400
[Amit Varma]: or garments plus textiles, stop quote. And you also talk about how you know, our self

01:15:09.400 --> 01:15:12.600
[Amit Varma]: image at one point in time used to be hey, we're a country with a high population and

01:15:12.600 --> 01:15:19.240
[Amit Varma]: food scarcity. That's completely changed. We can actually be an agricultural trade superpower

01:15:19.240 --> 01:15:24.280
[Amit Varma]: of the world. Elaborate on that with me because it just seems to me to be a win win from every

01:15:24.280 --> 01:15:29.200
[Amit Varma]: possible angle. It could reform our agricultural sector, it could give our farmers security

01:15:29.200 --> 01:15:33.560
[Amit Varma]: and access to greater markets. And it would also be great for national pride, we could

01:15:33.560 --> 01:15:35.200
[Amit Varma]: be feeding the world.

01:15:35.200 --> 01:15:42.640
[Guest]: So there is an old strain of export pessimism in India. Okay, so it is the insecurity of

01:15:42.640 --> 01:15:47.360
[Guest]: people in India that we think that we are clueless and we will not be able to compete

01:15:47.360 --> 01:15:51.960
[Guest]: in world markets. And over and over this has been proved wrong in one field after another.

01:15:51.960 --> 01:15:58.560
[Guest]: Manmohan Singh's PhD thesis in 1964 was one of the first intellectual products that questioned

01:15:58.560 --> 01:16:03.480
[Guest]: export pessimism and made the argument that we are rational economic agents like everywhere

01:16:03.480 --> 01:16:10.080
[Guest]: else in the world. And it's a matter of making prices work correctly and notably not having

01:16:10.080 --> 01:16:15.000
[Guest]: central bank manipulation of the exchange rate. And then we will get the ability to

01:16:15.000 --> 01:16:17.200
[Guest]: export just like anybody else.

01:16:17.200 --> 01:16:24.760
[Guest]: So in this retreat away from export pessimism into a more optimistic frame of mind, today

01:16:24.760 --> 01:16:30.240
[Guest]: in India, we see people like us feeling confident that we can do some modern things, that we

01:16:30.240 --> 01:16:36.600
[Guest]: can do software, we can do some business process outsourcing, we can make automobile components

01:16:36.600 --> 01:16:42.320
[Guest]: and we can make cars. Okay, that kind of confidence has seeped into India. But what my article

01:16:42.320 --> 01:16:47.180
[Guest]: was hoping to point out is that actually there is a wonderful miracle that is going on, which

01:16:47.180 --> 01:16:54.280
[Guest]: is agricultural exports from India. So in the 10 years leading up to 2016-17, we had

01:16:54.280 --> 01:17:00.880
[Guest]: huge growth rates of agricultural export. And if you pause to think why, actually the

01:17:00.880 --> 01:17:07.000
[Guest]: logic comes through very nicely. So one element is that given the Indian weather, land is

01:17:07.000 --> 01:17:12.040
[Guest]: viable around the year. So there is good sunlight around the year and there is no difficulty

01:17:12.040 --> 01:17:17.120
[Guest]: at any time of the year you can be doing agriculture. So the effective landmass available in India

01:17:17.120 --> 01:17:18.120
[Guest]: is very large.

01:17:18.120 --> 01:17:23.120
[Guest]: And the second idea is that a lot of modern high value agriculture is actually quite labor

01:17:23.120 --> 01:17:31.040
[Guest]: intensive. It's difficult to mechanize making cotton. It's difficult to mechanize making

01:17:31.040 --> 01:17:36.880
[Guest]: tomatoes. It's difficult to mechanize flowers and herbs and so on. So there are things that

01:17:36.880 --> 01:17:42.600
[Guest]: are more industrializable like wheat, where frankly what you want is a one kilometer by

01:17:42.600 --> 01:17:47.000
[Guest]: one kilometer farm and you want these gigantic machines which will do the whole thing. So

01:17:47.000 --> 01:17:52.520
[Guest]: that is a very capital intensive form of agriculture. And the moment I say capital intensive and

01:17:52.520 --> 01:17:57.560
[Guest]: labor intensive, I wish to appeal to trade theory. That's what trade theory is all about.

01:17:57.560 --> 01:18:02.360
[Guest]: That you want to do capital intensive agriculture in a place like Canada, where people have

01:18:02.360 --> 01:18:06.840
[Guest]: farms that are multiple square kilometers and millions of dollars of farm equipment

01:18:06.840 --> 01:18:11.600
[Guest]: and with very little labor, they grow wheat. So wheat is really not our thing. We don't

01:18:11.600 --> 01:18:15.440
[Guest]: have a competitive advantage in doing wheat. Where we have a competitive advantage is in

01:18:15.440 --> 01:18:21.360
[Guest]: doing fruits, in doing vegetables, in doing animal husbandry and milk and so on.

01:18:21.360 --> 01:18:26.200
[Guest]: So there is so much that can be done out of India where we can utilize the fact that actually

01:18:26.200 --> 01:18:33.520
[Guest]: we have a large labor force. And so put all these pieces together, get to producing agricultural

01:18:33.520 --> 01:18:38.640
[Guest]: goods, put them on planes, put them on ships, get them out to the world. This is not just

01:18:38.640 --> 01:18:45.200
[Guest]: a hypothesis. This is the reality. As my article points out, we've had very high dollar values

01:18:45.200 --> 01:18:50.040
[Guest]: and growth rates in this field. And this is something that India can do. So we should

01:18:50.040 --> 01:18:53.840
[Guest]: not be so pessimistic. But then once again, it requires that we've got to get out of all

01:18:53.840 --> 01:19:01.200
[Guest]: these distortions. The entrepreneurial genius of Punjab and Haryana should be devoted to

01:19:01.200 --> 01:19:08.520
[Guest]: supplying tulips to Amsterdam and vegetables to Tokyo. Instead of that, we've got the lowest

01:19:08.520 --> 01:19:13.100
[Guest]: value product of the whole world, namely wheat and rice being done in Punjab and Haryana.

01:19:13.100 --> 01:19:15.240
[Guest]: And that is the failure of policy.

01:19:15.240 --> 01:19:21.120
[Amit Varma]: That's extremely well put. And what you also kind of point out is that you talk about the

01:19:21.120 --> 01:19:25.000
[Amit Varma]: four themes of internationalism in the context of agriculture. And one, of course, what you

01:19:25.000 --> 01:19:29.560
[Amit Varma]: just pointed out is specialization that, you know, these are wheat and rice is not what

01:19:29.560 --> 01:19:34.160
[Amit Varma]: we should be making in such quantities. And like you pointed out, you know, the farmers

01:19:34.160 --> 01:19:39.240
[Amit Varma]: of Punjab supplying vegetables to Tokyo is quite a thought. But yeah, everybody will

01:19:39.240 --> 01:19:44.000
[Amit Varma]: find the niche that is most profitable for themselves. What you also point out your second

01:19:44.000 --> 01:19:48.680
[Amit Varma]: theme is on the political economy where you write, quote, the domestic policy process

01:19:48.680 --> 01:19:54.240
[Amit Varma]: can degenerate into a dysfunctional political economy, where special interest groups dominate.

01:19:54.240 --> 01:19:58.220
[Amit Varma]: Integrating into the global economy helps create a new dynamic. It becomes easier to

01:19:58.220 --> 01:20:03.800
[Amit Varma]: form coalitions in India across many different special interest groups aligned around success

01:20:03.800 --> 01:20:08.960
[Amit Varma]: in exporting, stop quote. So sort of elaborate on this a little bit for me, like what does

01:20:08.960 --> 01:20:13.480
[Amit Varma]: the current landscape look like in terms of agricultural policy and interest groups? And

01:20:13.480 --> 01:20:18.560
[Amit Varma]: how would that change if the incentives of all farmers suddenly change? If you know that,

01:20:18.560 --> 01:20:21.860
[Amit Varma]: you know, international trade is encouraged and that there won't be arbitrary bans on

01:20:21.860 --> 01:20:24.560
[Amit Varma]: X or Y, you know, how does the landscape change then?

01:20:24.560 --> 01:20:32.560
[Guest]: This is an old idea from Jagdish Bhagwati and Kruger, D. N. Srinivasan, who observed

01:20:32.560 --> 01:20:38.240
[Guest]: that when you get to exporting, it aligns domestic political economy in a more sensible

01:20:38.240 --> 01:20:43.840
[Guest]: direction. So in an inward-looking economy, in a more self-reliant economy, in a more

01:20:43.840 --> 01:20:48.760
[Guest]: import substitution economy, you tend to have a zero-sum game of local constituencies fighting

01:20:48.760 --> 01:20:52.880
[Guest]: with each other to grab a bigger share of the pie. Whereas when you are outward-oriented,

01:20:52.880 --> 01:20:57.720
[Guest]: when you're thinking that we have powerful lobbies in the country that are trying to

01:20:57.720 --> 01:21:04.280
[Guest]: make more money by exporting, then the behavior of those lobbies is to scream at the policymakers

01:21:04.280 --> 01:21:08.880
[Guest]: trying to resolve the bottlenecks that hold them back. And that creates a more positive

01:21:08.880 --> 01:21:15.880
[Guest]: kind of political economy conflict. So applied into the field of agriculture, there are more

01:21:15.880 --> 01:21:22.000
[Guest]: internationalized commodities in India, where frankly there is international trade and there's

01:21:22.000 --> 01:21:27.400
[Guest]: better integration with the world economy. And there has been more sanity in those areas

01:21:27.400 --> 01:21:33.440
[Guest]: as compared to the more inward-oriented areas where we fundamentally switch off the world

01:21:33.440 --> 01:21:36.980
[Guest]: political economy and then you get the worst of the Indian political economy.

01:21:36.980 --> 01:21:40.680
[Amit Varma]: And what you also pointed out is that, you know, at one point in that article, you write

01:21:40.680 --> 01:21:46.000
[Amit Varma]: about how another facet of internationalism is sustained engagement, where you write,

01:21:46.000 --> 01:21:50.680
[Amit Varma]: quote, many have commented on how India is seen as an unreliable seller owing to periodic

01:21:50.680 --> 01:21:55.440
[Amit Varma]: bans on export. The problem runs much deeper than this. Exporting is not a simple matter.

01:21:55.440 --> 01:22:01.480
[Amit Varma]: It requires developing complex organizational capital and business relationships. And later

01:22:01.480 --> 01:22:05.720
[Amit Varma]: you write, our instinct of bans and unbans are born of the age of food insecurity. The

01:22:05.720 --> 01:22:11.240
[Amit Varma]: world has changed. India's population is not able to consume the food that India grows,

01:22:11.240 --> 01:22:16.200
[Amit Varma]: stop quote. So, you know, at the policy level, if there is this sort of fundamental thinking

01:22:16.200 --> 01:22:21.600
[Amit Varma]: that there is a suspicion of exports perhaps, or there is a sense that so many people in

01:22:21.600 --> 01:22:26.120
[Amit Varma]: India are hungry, why should we allow exports? We should solve that first. You know, onion

01:22:26.120 --> 01:22:30.360
[Amit Varma]: prices are so high, why should we allow the export of onions, which will make onion prices

01:22:30.360 --> 01:22:36.440
[Amit Varma]: higher, which are entirely sort of wrong diagnosis of cause and effect, of course. But, you know,

01:22:36.440 --> 01:22:41.080
[Amit Varma]: that kind of policy thinking is still entrenched or do you find that it is, is there hope of

01:22:41.080 --> 01:22:48.000
[Amit Varma]: change happening there? And also, are farmers actually agitating for that kind of change?

01:22:48.000 --> 01:22:52.800
[Guest]: This thinking is very entrenched. What I have written is unusual. There are a few economists

01:22:52.800 --> 01:22:58.000
[Guest]: who are thinking in these ways. For me personally, it was Kirit Parekh who first opened my eyes

01:22:58.000 --> 01:23:03.920
[Guest]: to the possibilities of international trade and agriculture. For me also, when I used

01:23:03.920 --> 01:23:08.120
[Guest]: to have this schizophrenic idea that international trade is great for everything, but agriculture

01:23:08.120 --> 01:23:13.120
[Guest]: is special. And it was Kirit Parekh who helped me to see that no, all the standard knowledge

01:23:13.120 --> 01:23:17.720
[Guest]: and understanding of gains from trade, of international trade, of specialization applies

01:23:17.720 --> 01:23:23.680
[Guest]: equally in the field of agriculture. And there are very big gains to be had by going down

01:23:23.680 --> 01:23:28.280
[Guest]: that route. Jaswant Singh had a very nice phrase. He used to call it the psychology

01:23:28.280 --> 01:23:33.840
[Guest]: of scarcity. He used to say that India has become big in some ways and we've not yet

01:23:33.840 --> 01:23:40.280
[Guest]: lost the shackles of the mind where we think that there is scarcity. And I think that there's

01:23:40.280 --> 01:23:45.000
[Guest]: a certain growing up that needs to take place in our mind. I would also like to coldly make

01:23:45.000 --> 01:23:52.600
[Guest]: a distinction between hunger and agriculture. So there is a poverty problem in India. There's

01:23:52.600 --> 01:23:57.840
[Guest]: no question that there is a poverty problem in India. And for an analogy, I would say

01:23:57.840 --> 01:24:02.440
[Guest]: consider the United States. There is a poverty problem in the United States. There are many

01:24:02.440 --> 01:24:07.240
[Guest]: people in the United States who go hungry. But the fact that there is hunger in the United

01:24:07.240 --> 01:24:13.360
[Guest]: States does not in any way impinge on agriculture policy in the United States. They're two separate

01:24:13.360 --> 01:24:20.000
[Guest]: problems. So yeah, we should do more to solve poverty problems. There are many, many elements

01:24:20.000 --> 01:24:27.400
[Guest]: of how we can do things that will change poverty. Most notably, can we grow GDP? Can we expand

01:24:27.400 --> 01:24:34.040
[Guest]: the overall pie so that humble, low-skilled jobs in India generate higher and higher wages?

01:24:34.040 --> 01:24:38.000
[Guest]: There is a great discussion to be had around poverty. But for a moment, let me stick to

01:24:38.000 --> 01:24:42.640
[Guest]: the counterpoint of consider a country like the UK. There is a poverty problem in the

01:24:42.640 --> 01:24:47.040
[Guest]: UK. There are people in the UK going hungry. But that doesn't mean that you have to choke

01:24:47.040 --> 01:24:53.080
[Guest]: exports of food from the UK to the European Union. They're two separate things. We don't

01:24:53.080 --> 01:24:56.560
[Guest]: need to mix them up. We should understand these are private decisions. These are private

01:24:56.560 --> 01:25:03.760
[Guest]: markets. So if I make bananas, I should have the ability to produce bananas with the best

01:25:03.760 --> 01:25:08.800
[Guest]: focus and technology that I'm able to bring to it and develop supply chains through which

01:25:08.800 --> 01:25:14.400
[Guest]: I'm able to sell bananas into the highest-priced outlet that I can somewhere in the world.

01:25:14.400 --> 01:25:18.760
[Guest]: And that is the best thing that can happen to my income. And the fact that there is an

01:25:18.760 --> 01:25:25.640
[Guest]: Indian buyer of bananas does not generate reasons to damage me. So if you just think

01:25:25.640 --> 01:25:31.200
[Guest]: of the interests of every single farm producer, can we create conditions under which they

01:25:31.200 --> 01:25:35.960
[Guest]: get the best possible realization? And when they do specialization and they change their

01:25:35.960 --> 01:25:40.840
[Guest]: cropping patterns, most notably away from wheat and rice into other things, they will

01:25:40.840 --> 01:25:45.800
[Guest]: actually get to higher value things. So it's in the interest of the farmers to do this.

01:25:45.800 --> 01:25:51.040
[Guest]: And it's a bit of a mystery to me why this has gone wrong. And while I'm on this subject,

01:25:51.040 --> 01:25:59.120
[Guest]: I also want to emphasize there are such giant opportunities in dairy and in meat. So this

01:25:59.120 --> 01:26:04.360
[Guest]: is a vast country where there can be so much co-production of dairy. So I think India has

01:26:04.360 --> 01:26:10.320
[Guest]: got a great thing going where the agricultural residue of every farm is used to keep six

01:26:10.320 --> 01:26:17.040
[Guest]: cows. And we've got these sourcing networks where firms like Amul, firms like Britannia

01:26:17.040 --> 01:26:23.280
[Guest]: run the entire machinery going deep into rural India where they are sourcing milk. And this

01:26:23.280 --> 01:26:29.080
[Guest]: can easily turn into value-added things in the future, whether it is SMP, skim milk powder,

01:26:29.080 --> 01:26:33.600
[Guest]: or it is cheese or whatever. There is such large opportunities to dominate the world

01:26:33.600 --> 01:26:36.960
[Guest]: market in these things which are possible out of India.

01:26:36.960 --> 01:26:41.520
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. And I'd again like to sort of underscore the almost counterintuitive point that the

01:26:41.520 --> 01:26:47.160
[Amit Varma]: hunger problems that you see in India are not because of inadequate agricultural production.

01:26:47.160 --> 01:26:50.840
[Amit Varma]: Because you know, the statistic that I gave out in my last episode and that I wrote about

01:26:50.840 --> 01:26:56.160
[Amit Varma]: at one point is that in India, 3000 children die of starvation every single day. That you

01:26:56.160 --> 01:27:00.560
[Amit Varma]: know, more than one in four kids below a certain age is malnourished. There is clearly a hunger

01:27:00.560 --> 01:27:04.000
[Amit Varma]: and food problem, but it's got nothing to do with agricultural production. It's got

01:27:04.000 --> 01:27:08.000
[Amit Varma]: something to do with poverty. How you solve the problem of poverty is, like you said,

01:27:08.000 --> 01:27:12.520
[Amit Varma]: the whole pie goes larger and the economy grows. And part of the puzzle of that is solving

01:27:12.520 --> 01:27:18.720
[Amit Varma]: the problem of agriculture. And if agriculture grows massively, then you know, so will incomes

01:27:18.720 --> 01:27:22.120
[Amit Varma]: at the bottom of the chain as well.

01:27:22.120 --> 01:27:27.720
[Guest]: And also labor intensity. So if you are in Punjab growing wheat, then you will mechanize

01:27:27.720 --> 01:27:32.920
[Guest]: it and there will be less employment for poor people. Whereas if you're in Punjab and you're

01:27:32.920 --> 01:27:37.600
[Guest]: growing tulips, then you will have to hire more people because growing tulips is labor

01:27:37.600 --> 01:27:43.920
[Guest]: intensive. So we've done the exactly wrong thing that we have by having barriers to trade.

01:27:43.920 --> 01:27:47.600
[Guest]: We are doing capital intensive things of the kind that should just not be done in India.

01:27:47.600 --> 01:27:51.720
[Guest]: It's an old story. We've seen this movie before in every other part of the country, but that

01:27:51.720 --> 01:27:56.360
[Guest]: same movie is playing out in agriculture. That by opening up to international trade,

01:27:56.360 --> 01:28:02.480
[Guest]: we will get a reallocation towards more labor intensity. And so the landowner in India will

01:28:02.480 --> 01:28:09.840
[Guest]: hire more poor people to do agricultural work and thereby we will elevate the poverty problem.

01:28:09.840 --> 01:28:15.240
[Amit Varma]: That's a profound point. Let's, you know, moving on from international trade. Now let's

01:28:15.240 --> 01:28:20.760
[Amit Varma]: talk about trade within India, which is one of the things that the farm bills attempt

01:28:20.760 --> 01:28:25.960
[Amit Varma]: to address. Tell me a little bit about what the sort of problems here were.

01:28:25.960 --> 01:28:32.400
[Guest]: We in India built a grid of restrictions against the movement of agricultural commodities within

01:28:32.400 --> 01:28:39.560
[Guest]: the country. Okay. And there are broadly two or three groups of interferences. So the first

01:28:39.560 --> 01:28:44.840
[Guest]: and most famous interference is the APMC. Okay. So this is a 1950s idea. I have heard

01:28:44.840 --> 01:28:50.000
[Guest]: that it was pushed by the World Bank into many countries, including India. And the idea

01:28:50.000 --> 01:28:54.600
[Guest]: is that the government will create a monopoly spot market. So there is the Mandi that's

01:28:54.600 --> 01:28:59.920
[Guest]: created where buying and selling shall be done. And of course the power of the state

01:28:59.920 --> 01:29:06.120
[Guest]: is used so that you use state power to penalize anybody doing a transaction that is not at

01:29:06.120 --> 01:29:11.640
[Guest]: the Mandi. So we've created this artificial monopoly called the Mandi. And then sure enough,

01:29:11.640 --> 01:29:17.440
[Guest]: there's a bunch of people who exert disproportionate power at the Mandi and give very poor realizations

01:29:17.440 --> 01:29:23.680
[Guest]: to the farmers. So this is one class of barriers which interferes with domestic trade. This

01:29:23.680 --> 01:29:28.240
[Guest]: is the micro restriction. Then we have many, many barriers which interfere with the movement

01:29:28.240 --> 01:29:34.080
[Guest]: of goods between states. Okay. And these range from outright bans to what are called technical

01:29:34.080 --> 01:29:37.680
[Guest]: barriers in the field of international trade. So if you want to carry a truck of cotton

01:29:37.680 --> 01:29:41.400
[Guest]: from Maharashtra to Karnataka, the Maharashtra government makes it difficult because somehow

01:29:41.400 --> 01:29:46.400
[Guest]: the Maharashtra government has an idea that we want to double quotes reserve this cotton

01:29:46.400 --> 01:29:50.800
[Guest]: for mills in Maharashtra. And I think this is a deeply, deeply pernicious idea. Okay.

01:29:50.800 --> 01:29:55.600
[Guest]: The whole point of being the Republic of India is that we should have free movement of all

01:29:55.600 --> 01:30:00.880
[Guest]: economic activities across the country. People should move, goods should move, and so on.

01:30:00.880 --> 01:30:04.760
[Guest]: But there are many, many restrictions that hamper the movement of goods across the country.

01:30:04.760 --> 01:30:09.160
[Guest]: Either they're explicit bans or they're all kinds of softer restrictions, which bottom

01:30:09.160 --> 01:30:16.800
[Guest]: line generate interference into the freedom of trade. We see that quite vividly. For example,

01:30:16.800 --> 01:30:25.480
[Guest]: when we look at the divergence of prices between locations in India. So the price of a product

01:30:25.480 --> 01:30:31.080
[Guest]: in Pune versus the price of a product in Bhopal should be essentially the same within a band

01:30:31.080 --> 01:30:35.080
[Guest]: which reflects the cost of transportation between Pune and Bhopal. Other than that,

01:30:35.080 --> 01:30:39.000
[Guest]: there should be no differences. In fact, we see fairly large differences all across the

01:30:39.000 --> 01:30:44.360
[Guest]: country. And this is because there are these restrictions on the movement of goods. So

01:30:44.360 --> 01:30:49.960
[Guest]: this is the whole domestic trade agenda where partly we've created these little monopolies

01:30:49.960 --> 01:30:54.720
[Guest]: called the APMCs, which interfere with the ability of somebody else to come in and talk

01:30:54.720 --> 01:30:59.600
[Guest]: to a farmer and offer a better price. So why are we interfering in the economic freedom

01:30:59.600 --> 01:31:05.560
[Guest]: of the farmer is something that beats me. I would even be okay if somebody said, here,

01:31:05.560 --> 01:31:11.160
[Guest]: we'll build an APMC for you. And it's your choice that we use public money to build an

01:31:11.160 --> 01:31:15.120
[Guest]: APMC. So we've got some physical facility and some handling of agricultural goods and

01:31:15.120 --> 01:31:20.480
[Guest]: some way scales and storage and so on. And it's your choice that if you live X kilometers

01:31:20.480 --> 01:31:25.040
[Guest]: away from this, it might be convenient for you to come there. How did we cross the line

01:31:25.040 --> 01:31:30.680
[Guest]: to using coercion is something that beats me. In what universe are you better off coercing

01:31:30.680 --> 01:31:36.000
[Guest]: a farmer, saying that if you dare to do a transaction at any place other than the APMC,

01:31:36.000 --> 01:31:39.480
[Guest]: then the coercive power of the state will be used to inflict punishment upon you and

01:31:39.480 --> 01:31:45.240
[Guest]: upon your counterparty. That to me is really something that is unethical. How could anybody

01:31:45.240 --> 01:31:50.120
[Guest]: countenance this kind of thing? So these are the two elements of the domestic trade agenda.

01:31:50.120 --> 01:31:53.800
[Guest]: Free movement of goods all across the country and the APMCs.

01:31:53.800 --> 01:31:58.360
[Amit Varma]: So you know, I can't resist an opportunity to do some share-o-shirey on the show. So

01:31:58.360 --> 01:32:02.400
[Amit Varma]: just to talk about APMCs, which, you know, I had an episode with the farmer leader, Gunwant

01:32:02.400 --> 01:32:09.760
[Amit Varma]: Patil, a couple of years back. And he told me about this great share, which Sharad Joshi,

01:32:09.760 --> 01:32:16.880
[Amit Varma]: the great farmer leader, used to sort of, and this is something that a farmer is saying

01:32:16.880 --> 01:32:21.000
[Amit Varma]: to a consumer, and I'll explain the context of this after I go through this, and it runs

01:32:21.000 --> 01:32:34.800
[Amit Varma]: this way. To quickly translate for non-Hindi listeners, it translates this way, I die my

01:32:34.800 --> 01:32:40.080
[Amit Varma]: friend and so do you. I die my friend and so do you. I sell my produce cheap and die.

01:32:40.080 --> 01:32:44.640
[Amit Varma]: You pay so much that you die too. And the whole idea is that because of the APMC, the

01:32:44.640 --> 01:32:48.840
[Amit Varma]: farmer is selling too cheap and the consumer is buying too expensive because the APMC is

01:32:48.840 --> 01:32:54.920
[Amit Varma]: a monopsony. The only person who can buy from the farmer, a government mandated monopsony,

01:32:54.920 --> 01:32:57.600
[Amit Varma]: you're not allowed to sell anywhere else. So therefore, what happens is they can set

01:32:57.600 --> 01:33:02.920
[Amit Varma]: whatever price they want. Like at one point, I remember a report which spoke about how

01:33:02.920 --> 01:33:07.840
[Amit Varma]: farmers would sell tomatoes to the APMC at two rupees a kg and consumers would buy them

01:33:07.840 --> 01:33:12.280
[Amit Varma]: for 20 rupees. And this is just nuts. So you have the APMC taking 18 rupees, farmers are

01:33:12.280 --> 01:33:16.760
[Amit Varma]: getting paid two bucks, consumers are paying 20 bucks. What you could instead have had

01:33:16.760 --> 01:33:21.640
[Amit Varma]: is that if you had a competition of middlemen, and you could sell to whoever you wanted,

01:33:21.640 --> 01:33:25.960
[Amit Varma]: the competition of middlemen would ensure a situation where, for example, the farmer

01:33:25.960 --> 01:33:30.000
[Amit Varma]: instead of two rupees could sell his tomatoes for 10 bucks, and the consumer could buy them

01:33:30.000 --> 01:33:35.320
[Amit Varma]: for 12 bucks. Farmer benefits by eight rupees, consumer benefits by eight rupees, enormous

01:33:35.320 --> 01:33:39.440
[Amit Varma]: benefit. And we don't have that. And as far as you know, I can make out from this farm

01:33:39.440 --> 01:33:43.160
[Amit Varma]: sales, they haven't even done away with the APMC. They've said the APMC is there as an

01:33:43.160 --> 01:33:48.400
[Amit Varma]: option. But now you're allowed to sell anywhere else as well. Is that a correct understanding?

01:33:48.400 --> 01:33:54.200
[Guest]: Yes. So this is a key point that for all practical purposes, there may be many parts in India

01:33:54.200 --> 01:33:58.760
[Guest]: where a farmer is really stuck. And you have no choice but to go to the friendly neighborhood

01:33:58.760 --> 01:34:05.640
[Guest]: APMC, which has land, which has facilities, where state power was used many years ago

01:34:05.640 --> 01:34:10.560
[Guest]: in the establishment of the APMC. Once that is done, I would be the one complaining about

01:34:10.560 --> 01:34:14.960
[Guest]: competition policy. I'd be saying that a few blocks are that APMC have market power and

01:34:14.960 --> 01:34:19.940
[Guest]: we need to go do something about it. The only thing that we're fighting about right now

01:34:19.940 --> 01:34:24.660
[Guest]: is don't make it illegal for somebody else to deal with the farmer directly. It's such

01:34:24.660 --> 01:34:30.320
[Amit Varma]: a basic conception of economic freedom. Yeah. And also, you know, one criticism that has

01:34:30.320 --> 01:34:34.080
[Amit Varma]: come about, you know, this particular reform, allowing the farmer to sell to anyone instead

01:34:34.080 --> 01:34:37.640
[Amit Varma]: of forcing him to sell to one person. And one of the criticisms is that, oh, this is

01:34:37.640 --> 01:34:42.720
[Amit Varma]: corporatization, corporates will take over, there'll be an Ambani and Adani monopoly,

01:34:42.720 --> 01:34:47.320
[Amit Varma]: which seems to me to be a bizarre criticism. First of all, all these interactions between

01:34:47.320 --> 01:34:53.080
[Amit Varma]: the farmers and whoever he or she is negotiating with, these are all voluntary interactions.

01:34:53.080 --> 01:34:58.280
[Amit Varma]: And the farmer still has a choice of going to the APMC and selling at the MSP and so

01:34:58.280 --> 01:35:03.160
[Amit Varma]: on. And it's just that you've expanded their choice, you've not taken anything away. And

01:35:03.160 --> 01:35:08.640
[Amit Varma]: the other aspect of looking at it is that after the liberalization of 91, in which area

01:35:08.640 --> 01:35:13.680
[Amit Varma]: which was liberalized, did you see a corporate monopoly squeezing the poor guy? Instead,

01:35:13.680 --> 01:35:17.800
[Amit Varma]: what you had was, it was great for consumers, it was great for producers, it was great for

01:35:17.800 --> 01:35:21.800
[Amit Varma]: suppliers, it was just fantastic all the way around. So I don't know where this criticism

01:35:21.800 --> 01:35:24.240
[Amit Varma]: comes from and where you go from here to there.

01:35:24.240 --> 01:35:29.280
[Guest]: So if some Ambani, Adani organizations actually reached out to some farmers and made bids

01:35:29.280 --> 01:35:34.360
[Guest]: to them saying, I'll buy your tomatoes at four rupees, I would say, hey, how wonderful,

01:35:34.360 --> 01:35:38.880
[Guest]: as compared to going to an APMC and selling the tomatoes at two rupees. So again, there

01:35:38.880 --> 01:35:44.320
[Guest]: is no force. Nobody's forcing anybody to do anything. It's just removing the Indian state

01:35:44.320 --> 01:35:50.920
[Guest]: from coercing farmers and anybody else that they might dare contract with saying that

01:35:50.920 --> 01:35:56.360
[Guest]: this is illegal. That is something that is phenomenally bad and that is something that

01:35:56.360 --> 01:35:58.560
[Guest]: is sought to be eliminated.

01:35:58.560 --> 01:36:01.960
[Amit Varma]: And do these farm bills also do something about the second aspect of it, which, you

01:36:01.960 --> 01:36:06.800
[Amit Varma]: know, interstate trading and trading anywhere else you want and, you know, accessing prices

01:36:06.800 --> 01:36:10.040
[Amit Varma]: elsewhere. Do they also do something with regard to that?

01:36:10.040 --> 01:36:14.640
[Guest]: It's a beginning on those things. So I see a long agenda on domestic trade that it will

01:36:14.640 --> 01:36:18.960
[Guest]: not get solved overnight. So as an example, I talked about APMC. Okay, the fact is in

01:36:18.960 --> 01:36:23.440
[Guest]: most regions of India, the APMC is the only game in town. So realistically, the APMC is

01:36:23.440 --> 01:36:26.760
[Guest]: going to be an important part of this landscape for a while. And we need to do many, many

01:36:26.760 --> 01:36:31.800
[Guest]: things. So I think of domestic trade as an agenda, as a journey where we will have to

01:36:31.800 --> 01:36:36.240
[Guest]: fix many things. But, you know, you got to start somewhere.

01:36:36.240 --> 01:36:40.480
[Amit Varma]: And you've pointed to Article 301 elsewhere, where in one of your pieces, you wrote, quote,

01:36:40.480 --> 01:36:45.080
[Amit Varma]: a key idea lies in utilizing Article 301 of the Constitution of India, which states that

01:36:45.080 --> 01:36:49.540
[Amit Varma]: trade and commerce throughout India shall be free, stop quote. And therefore, it seems

01:36:49.540 --> 01:36:53.880
[Amit Varma]: to me to my delight that all these restrictions which have existed on trade and commerce in

01:36:53.880 --> 01:36:56.800
[Amit Varma]: the past are therefore unconstitutional, right?

01:36:56.800 --> 01:37:02.560
[Guest]: Well, so let me look at this precisely in the present debates also. So there is a lot

01:37:02.560 --> 01:37:09.280
[Guest]: of debate around agriculture as a state subject. Okay. And you know, my views, well, I am a

01:37:09.280 --> 01:37:15.200
[Guest]: great admirer of the federal and decentralized nature of the Republic of India. And I'm always

01:37:15.200 --> 01:37:21.160
[Guest]: looking for policy pathways in which we can deepen that decentralization, send more power

01:37:21.160 --> 01:37:25.040
[Guest]: and more functions down to state governments and city governments, because that's really

01:37:25.040 --> 01:37:29.600
[Guest]: the best way to organize this country. This country is too vast to be ruled by any one

01:37:29.600 --> 01:37:35.520
[Guest]: union government or one new Delhi. So I'm very sympathetic to the decentralization agenda.

01:37:35.520 --> 01:37:41.520
[Guest]: However, there is also an element in the Constitution and one that legitimately belongs, which is

01:37:41.520 --> 01:37:46.320
[Guest]: on problems of interstate commerce. Okay. So in India, that is Article 301. For example,

01:37:46.320 --> 01:37:50.560
[Guest]: in the United States, we would all tend to know that in the Constitution, there is this

01:37:50.560 --> 01:37:55.480
[Guest]: issue about barriers to interstate commerce, that it is not okay to introduce barriers

01:37:55.480 --> 01:38:01.400
[Guest]: to interstate commerce, either through federal law or through state law. So there is a union

01:38:01.400 --> 01:38:07.680
[Guest]: government role in interfering with and disrupting barriers to interstate commerce. And that

01:38:07.680 --> 01:38:13.520
[Guest]: is the legitimate domain of the union government. And these laws that have had restrictions

01:38:13.520 --> 01:38:19.320
[Guest]: have in the past got approval of the president of India, because that was required as they

01:38:19.320 --> 01:38:23.880
[Guest]: would have otherwise infringed on Article 301. So I just want to say that the laws that

01:38:23.880 --> 01:38:28.880
[Guest]: are sought to be changed by these three farm bills had gone through the same Constitution

01:38:28.880 --> 01:38:34.400
[Guest]: of India, had gone through approval of the president of India and of the union, because

01:38:34.400 --> 01:38:42.200
[Guest]: this is the domain of the union. And today, the parliament is legislating in what is legitimately

01:38:42.200 --> 01:38:47.160
[Guest]: the province of the parliament. So I do not think that there is anything being done that

01:38:47.160 --> 01:38:55.200
[Guest]: is wrong. And if you will put a link to the paper, my colleagues and I wrote this paper

01:38:55.200 --> 01:39:02.160
[Guest]: in 2015 and 2016, well before these bills were done. And two of my four co-authors,

01:39:02.160 --> 01:39:10.160
[Guest]: Shubo Roy and Anirudh Burman are lawyers and have enormous specialized technical expertise

01:39:10.160 --> 01:39:16.720
[Guest]: on these questions. And we feel quite clear that this is the domain, this is the legitimate

01:39:16.720 --> 01:39:20.040
[Guest]: domain of the parliament in forming legislation.

01:39:20.040 --> 01:39:26.040
[Amit Varma]: Great. Let us talk about the farm bills now. And it is very complicated and nuanced. And

01:39:26.040 --> 01:39:32.400
[Amit Varma]: I want to talk about it in a number of different dimensions, some of which we will know less

01:39:32.400 --> 01:39:37.040
[Amit Varma]: about than others. But nevertheless, one that you would know about quite thoroughly is the

01:39:37.040 --> 01:39:41.560
[Amit Varma]: content of it. You know, that is a sort of first of four areas that I would like to address.

01:39:41.560 --> 01:39:47.440
[Amit Varma]: So when it comes to the content of the farm bills, is there anything there that is problematic

01:39:47.440 --> 01:39:51.740
[Amit Varma]: or short-sighted or goes in the wrong direction? Or would you say that it all broadly goes

01:39:51.740 --> 01:39:54.760
[Amit Varma]: in the right direction? Like earlier, you said you're 90% in agreement with…

01:39:54.760 --> 01:39:56.720
[Amit Varma]: It all broadly goes in the right direction.

01:39:56.720 --> 01:40:00.120
[Amit Varma]: It all broadly goes in the right direction. My other sort of criticism of this is the

01:40:00.120 --> 01:40:05.320
[Amit Varma]: process because the one area where I find myself quite aghast is the way that it was

01:40:05.320 --> 01:40:10.740
[Amit Varma]: pushed through parliament, the way that, you know, dissent is not engaged with, that anyone

01:40:10.740 --> 01:40:17.880
[Amit Varma]: who protests is by default painted as anti-national. And just a vituperative tone of the response

01:40:17.880 --> 01:40:23.480
[Amit Varma]: to criticism seems to me to be extremely anti-democratic. And at some level, I guess, there's a federalism

01:40:23.480 --> 01:40:27.320
[Amit Varma]: argument also that in many of these areas, let the states make up their own mind. What

01:40:27.320 --> 01:40:32.320
[Amit Varma]: is your sense of the process of this? Is there something that the government could have done

01:40:32.320 --> 01:40:37.480
[Amit Varma]: differently? Is there a fundamental tendency within the government to think in a particular

01:40:37.480 --> 01:40:42.040
[Amit Varma]: way, which has led to, you know, the bills being carried out like this? Because what

01:40:42.040 --> 01:40:47.480
[Amit Varma]: it seems to me is that an essential component of liberalism, now understand that these bills,

01:40:47.480 --> 01:40:50.960
[Amit Varma]: in the sense that we understand liberalism in terms of increasing individual freedom

01:40:50.960 --> 01:40:56.280
[Amit Varma]: and reducing state coercion, the content of the bills is fairly liberal, but the end doesn't

01:40:56.280 --> 01:41:00.720
[Amit Varma]: always justify the means. And it seems to me that there is something deeply flawed with

01:41:00.720 --> 01:41:02.120
[Amit Varma]: the means. What are your thoughts on that?

01:41:02.120 --> 01:41:06.480
[Guest]: So I wish to say three things on this subject. The first is where we were a moment ago, that

01:41:06.480 --> 01:41:14.600
[Guest]: there needs to be much more of a public policy debate and discourse. And this is true, not

01:41:14.600 --> 01:41:21.560
[Guest]: just of agriculture, it is true of all fields. In my opinion, we in India are in a declining

01:41:21.560 --> 01:41:28.560
[Guest]: phase of the intellectualism and the public debate and discourse surrounding a lot of

01:41:28.560 --> 01:41:36.880
[Guest]: fields. We don't have much of a public sphere, and these bills emerge pristine from some

01:41:36.880 --> 01:41:41.600
[Guest]: government person who drafts the bills. Okay. So, and I think that that's not a healthy

01:41:41.600 --> 01:41:46.280
[Guest]: way to proceed. Partly from an intellectual point of view, that debate and discussion

01:41:46.280 --> 01:41:50.920
[Guest]: always improves work. Okay. Nobody is smart enough to figure out these things. Okay. We

01:41:50.920 --> 01:41:57.120
[Guest]: each of us, that if I was the policymaker, I would be the beneficiary from a vibrant

01:41:57.120 --> 01:42:02.120
[Guest]: process of public discussion and debate. As I have been involved in many, many episodes

01:42:02.120 --> 01:42:06.600
[Guest]: in the past, that the process of discussion, the process of debate, of putting something

01:42:06.600 --> 01:42:12.520
[Guest]: up in 100 seminars and conferences, chips away at the ideas and refines ideas and makes

01:42:12.520 --> 01:42:17.200
[Guest]: ideas better. So you get something that's a better quality product out of the process

01:42:17.200 --> 01:42:23.160
[Guest]: of debate and discourse. And you end up politically sensitizing the broader community that, you

01:42:23.160 --> 01:42:27.240
[Guest]: know, this kind of stuff is in the Bible. So I think that's very important. Otherwise

01:42:27.240 --> 01:42:32.280
[Guest]: you suddenly spring surprises on people and, you know, needlessly that creates more of

01:42:32.280 --> 01:42:39.360
[Guest]: a sudden allergic response. This is my, the first point I'd like to make. The second point

01:42:39.360 --> 01:42:43.960
[Guest]: is also an economics point. And now I want to step back a little from these bills to

01:42:43.960 --> 01:42:48.960
[Guest]: go after the bigger problem of Punjab and Haryana. And here I'm reporting the thought

01:42:48.960 --> 01:42:53.360
[Guest]: process that I picked up in recent weeks through conversations with Vijay Kelkar. This is really

01:42:53.360 --> 01:42:58.760
[Guest]: Kelkar's idea. So I have been a part of the conversations and I agree with the thought.

01:42:58.760 --> 01:43:05.560
[Guest]: So Kelkar has been thinking that there is a weird equilibrium that Punjab and Haryana

01:43:05.560 --> 01:43:10.480
[Guest]: particularly are locked into, which is a combination of everything that you described, that there

01:43:10.480 --> 01:43:18.320
[Guest]: is free electricity, barriers to international trade, MSP. There's a whole machinery of farmers

01:43:18.320 --> 01:43:24.440
[Guest]: in Punjab who are locked into wheat and rice and who don't know any other way. Okay. And

01:43:24.440 --> 01:43:29.680
[Guest]: we must recognize the culpability, the complicity of the Indian state in doing this. And if

01:43:29.680 --> 01:43:38.440
[Guest]: you wish to make moral arguments, then after the 60s, 64, 65 and 65, 66, two consecutive

01:43:38.440 --> 01:43:43.520
[Guest]: droughts and see Subramaniam and the green revolution and all the amazing things that

01:43:43.520 --> 01:43:47.840
[Guest]: were done in that period by policymakers, you could almost make the claim that, look,

01:43:47.840 --> 01:43:52.000
[Guest]: it is Punjab and Haryana that protected the rest of India, that rescued the rest of India,

01:43:52.000 --> 01:43:58.520
[Guest]: that bailed out India in a time of high population growth by producing those surges of agricultural

01:43:58.520 --> 01:44:03.760
[Guest]: output that was so desperately required in India of that age. Otherwise we would be down

01:44:03.760 --> 01:44:12.120
[Guest]: to PL 480 charity from the United States to eat. Okay. So that was a different time. And

01:44:12.120 --> 01:44:19.280
[Guest]: at that time, maybe it made sense to orchestrate this electricity and MSP and high yielding

01:44:19.280 --> 01:44:25.880
[Guest]: varieties and subsidized fertilizer to just get Punjab and Haryana to become the agricultural

01:44:25.880 --> 01:44:33.360
[Guest]: heartland of India. And they fed the entire country. Now, there is a problem in abruptly

01:44:33.360 --> 01:44:39.760
[Guest]: yanking that. Okay. So if you abruptly yank that, then it's not fair because it's a big

01:44:39.760 --> 01:44:45.360
[Guest]: disruption that's placed upon everybody in Punjab and Haryana. If you change one piece

01:44:45.360 --> 01:44:50.520
[Guest]: at a time, it's actually complicated because these are general equilibrium effects. There's

01:44:50.520 --> 01:44:57.120
[Guest]: no guarantee that if you fix one restraint at a time, that you will actually get gains

01:44:57.120 --> 01:45:01.720
[Guest]: in return for each one step at a time. That's a weird thing that happens with general equilibrium

01:45:01.720 --> 01:45:07.240
[Guest]: reasoning that if you remove the fertilizer subsidy and the electricity subsidy and the

01:45:07.240 --> 01:45:15.880
[Guest]: NREGS and the MSP and the domestic trade restrictions and the international trade restrictions and

01:45:15.880 --> 01:45:20.000
[Guest]: the malfunctioning of the futures markets, if you remove all these together, then I have

01:45:20.000 --> 01:45:23.920
[Guest]: no doubt that in two, three years, the system will find a new equilibrium where every farmer

01:45:23.920 --> 01:45:28.600
[Guest]: will be better off. But along the way, when you go one step at a time, there's no guarantee

01:45:28.600 --> 01:45:32.800
[Guest]: that things become better for the affected people. So you really need to see this as

01:45:32.800 --> 01:45:39.760
[Guest]: a part of a fuller strategy that we are going to move towards a market-oriented, internationalized

01:45:39.760 --> 01:45:43.920
[Guest]: agriculture. We're going to do it in these 10 steps over 10 years.

01:45:43.920 --> 01:45:49.560
[Guest]: And Kelkar argues that this is a bit like a structural adjustment program that the IMF

01:45:49.560 --> 01:45:55.520
[Guest]: and the World Bank put together for a country which has a horrendously messed up collection

01:45:55.520 --> 01:46:00.040
[Guest]: of policies. So if you want to fix all those policies, imagine that for 10 years, we are

01:46:00.040 --> 01:46:06.800
[Guest]: putting in public money to do direct cash transfers to individuals in Punjab and Haryana,

01:46:06.800 --> 01:46:11.840
[Guest]: where that money tapers away over a 10-year period. And bit by bit, over a five-year period,

01:46:11.840 --> 01:46:17.920
[Guest]: we are removing all these barriers. And through that way, we have managed an entire transition

01:46:17.920 --> 01:46:20.200
[Guest]: to coming up to a new system.

01:46:20.200 --> 01:46:24.480
[Guest]: So where we are going wrong today is that we've removed one piece, and we don't have

01:46:24.480 --> 01:46:29.240
[Guest]: a game plan for the full thing. And the game plan for the full thing needs to bring the

01:46:29.240 --> 01:46:34.640
[Guest]: worldview of a structural adjustment program, rather than just saying that, sorry, screw

01:46:34.640 --> 01:46:38.800
[Guest]: you, we're just going to do all this. And that's not a very good way to do things in

01:46:38.800 --> 01:46:39.800
[Guest]: a democracy.

01:46:39.800 --> 01:46:45.280
[Guest]: And my last point is exactly where you left off, that politics is the art of negotiation.

01:46:45.280 --> 01:46:51.320
[Guest]: Politics is the process of bringing people together and finding deals and finding contracts,

01:46:51.320 --> 01:46:57.080
[Guest]: finding middle roads that make sense. And surely, there should have been ways to bring

01:46:57.080 --> 01:47:01.840
[Guest]: people to the table and negotiate in good faith and find better outcomes, particularly

01:47:01.840 --> 01:47:07.600
[Guest]: when the hand of cards is so good. These three bills are so good, they are only a step in

01:47:07.600 --> 01:47:13.720
[Guest]: the correct direction. It's a failure of negotiation that it turned into so much anger and so much

01:47:13.720 --> 01:47:16.360
[Guest]: unhappiness and so much partisan tribalism.

01:47:16.360 --> 01:47:21.680
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, it's a massive failure of negotiation and of politics. Two aspects of this which

01:47:21.680 --> 01:47:27.080
[Amit Varma]: I want to kind of explore in a theoretical sense, where these specific bills are only

01:47:27.080 --> 01:47:32.440
[Amit Varma]: an illustration. One is a political ramification of big changes. So let's say you need to,

01:47:32.440 --> 01:47:35.920
[Amit Varma]: there are 10 changes you need to make together and then you know, everybody will be better

01:47:35.920 --> 01:47:41.240
[Amit Varma]: off. But the problem is that it's not visible to everyone that they will be better off and

01:47:41.240 --> 01:47:45.920
[Amit Varma]: they'd rather, you know, take the bird in hand and think about two in the bush right

01:47:45.920 --> 01:47:50.320
[Amit Varma]: now, especially those who are beneficiaries of the current system, whether they are, you

01:47:50.320 --> 01:47:56.400
[Amit Varma]: know, benefiting from the APMC monopsony or whatever. So then what happens is that anytime

01:47:56.400 --> 01:48:00.640
[Amit Varma]: you try something like this, if the short term losers, even if they're winners in the

01:48:00.640 --> 01:48:06.520
[Amit Varma]: long term, if the short term losers are going to kind of protest, then does that become

01:48:06.520 --> 01:48:11.640
[Amit Varma]: a roadblock for any kind of significant reform? Because no matter what you do, somebody will

01:48:11.640 --> 01:48:15.640
[Amit Varma]: feel that they're losing out in the short term. And in the partisan tribal atmosphere

01:48:15.640 --> 01:48:20.480
[Amit Varma]: of our modern times, the entire opposition, whoever it is at that point in time, will

01:48:20.480 --> 01:48:25.600
[Amit Varma]: rally around that particular aggrieved party and it then becomes difficult to move forward

01:48:25.600 --> 01:48:30.720
[Amit Varma]: at all. Is there then a danger of policy paralysis because of politics?

01:48:30.720 --> 01:48:41.040
[Guest]: So I think that it was Pratap Bhanumetha who said that when the ordinary consensual negotiation

01:48:41.040 --> 01:48:45.200
[Guest]: approach to politics, where there is a constant conversation that is kept alive, when that

01:48:45.200 --> 01:48:50.240
[Guest]: breaks down, then you're down to screaming in the streets as the only way out. So I feel

01:48:50.240 --> 01:48:57.400
[Guest]: that there's a deeper problem that we've got to rebuild the quiet comfort of people in

01:48:57.400 --> 01:49:01.720
[Guest]: the treasury benches talking to people in the opposition benches. Kelkar always says

01:49:01.720 --> 01:49:07.760
[Guest]: that a political party should go into opposition, but it should never go out of power. That

01:49:07.760 --> 01:49:11.480
[Guest]: opposition party should always have influence. They should always have a role. They should

01:49:11.480 --> 01:49:18.520
[Guest]: have a say. And the art of doing democratic politics in a liberal democracy is to carry

01:49:18.520 --> 01:49:24.360
[Guest]: people along. So this is something that we need to learn a lot more of what Vajpayee

01:49:24.360 --> 01:49:31.280
[Guest]: used to call coalition dharma. Why India worked well in coalitions led by people like Vajpayee

01:49:31.280 --> 01:49:37.120
[Guest]: or Gujarat or P. V. Narasimha Rao was that coalition dharma. Bring many people together,

01:49:37.120 --> 01:49:41.560
[Guest]: talk, negotiate, talk, negotiate. I think that there's a certain Indian middle class

01:49:41.560 --> 01:49:46.960
[Guest]: thing where we've started craving for a strong leader and somebody with that will just decisively

01:49:46.960 --> 01:49:53.400
[Guest]: go do things. And I think that is fundamentally incompatible with the reasonable narration

01:49:53.400 --> 01:49:56.120
[Guest]: of what liberal democracy is all about.

01:49:56.120 --> 01:50:02.720
[Amit Varma]: Also strikes me like, for example, when GST was announced on GST, of course, was, in theory,

01:50:02.720 --> 01:50:06.120
[Amit Varma]: something that would really help the economy and reduce a lot of the friction. And it was

01:50:06.120 --> 01:50:10.760
[Amit Varma]: great, but it was so badly implemented that it caused a lot of damage and continues to

01:50:10.760 --> 01:50:15.200
[Amit Varma]: cause damage to this day, much of which I see around me with all my friends who are

01:50:15.200 --> 01:50:20.360
[Amit Varma]: entrepreneurs and have factories or had factories, because it's been so damaging. And the thought

01:50:20.360 --> 01:50:26.260
[Amit Varma]: that struck me during that time is that even if you're moving from, say, one bad equilibrium

01:50:26.260 --> 01:50:31.920
[Amit Varma]: to another better equilibrium, there is a transaction cost to that movement itself that

01:50:31.920 --> 01:50:37.040
[Amit Varma]: in that movement, there can be so many unintended consequences and so many things going wrong,

01:50:37.040 --> 01:50:41.440
[Amit Varma]: because of all kinds of reasons, because of factors outside your control, unknown, unknown

01:50:41.440 --> 01:50:47.200
[Amit Varma]: state capacity, and so on, that in the end, you don't necessarily end up with either something

01:50:47.200 --> 01:50:53.840
[Amit Varma]: that is better or with something that justifies the shift in the first place. Is this something

01:50:53.840 --> 01:50:57.960
[Amit Varma]: that you think about while making policy? Because like the point that you pointed out

01:50:57.960 --> 01:51:02.520
[Amit Varma]: is that you can't in something in a machinery where so many things are broken, there's no

01:51:02.520 --> 01:51:06.560
[Amit Varma]: point piecemeal changing a couple of things here or three, four things here, you have

01:51:06.560 --> 01:51:12.580
[Amit Varma]: to overhaul the entire thing. So how does one think about that? And, you know, it seems

01:51:12.580 --> 01:51:19.440
[Amit Varma]: to me so daunting that just the daunting nature of what could happen is enough to make a politician

01:51:19.440 --> 01:51:23.560
[Amit Varma]: or a bureaucrat say that, hey, let me just make incremental differences to the status

01:51:23.560 --> 01:51:30.880
[Guest]: quo and try nothing drastic. So as somebody who was in the founding team of the GST in

01:51:30.880 --> 01:51:38.000
[Guest]: India, it is indeed really troubling and humbling to see how things didn't quite work out, like

01:51:38.000 --> 01:51:45.280
[Guest]: one would have anticipated. And I have no ready solution to how to play that GST kind

01:51:45.280 --> 01:51:50.320
[Guest]: of episode better. We just lost institutional memory. There was a whole bunch of people

01:51:50.320 --> 01:51:56.200
[Guest]: who knew about the GST. And then finally, when the negotiations were being done first

01:51:56.200 --> 01:52:02.240
[Guest]: with Pranam Mukherjee and then with Jaitley, the basic knowledge of GST had been lost.

01:52:02.240 --> 01:52:06.960
[Guest]: And so what was negotiated and what came out and what got implemented just seems to bear

01:52:06.960 --> 01:52:11.960
[Guest]: no resemblance to the early conception of what a GST is all about. So I think it was

01:52:11.960 --> 01:52:16.200
[Guest]: a failure of a policy community. And that takes you back to a deeper question, a bit

01:52:16.200 --> 01:52:21.140
[Guest]: like what I'm saying about the problems of a health policy community in similar fashion.

01:52:21.140 --> 01:52:26.600
[Guest]: We just did not have enough of a public finance policy community that would be able to think

01:52:26.600 --> 01:52:33.240
[Guest]: deeply about the GST and stay on the ball and stay on message on the subject of GST

01:52:33.240 --> 01:52:39.120
[Guest]: for 20 years, which is the kind of time horizon that is required to do that. That said, it's

01:52:39.120 --> 01:52:44.480
[Guest]: actually much easier in the field of agriculture because the agenda in agriculture is a much

01:52:44.480 --> 01:52:50.320
[Guest]: simpler agenda, what is sometimes called first generation reforms, which is just get the

01:52:50.320 --> 01:52:54.600
[Guest]: state out of the way. Those are much easier reforms to execute.

01:52:54.600 --> 01:53:01.040
[Guest]: So when all that has to be done is to have a stroke of the pen where there is a law which

01:53:01.040 --> 01:53:07.280
[Guest]: removes the barrier against a foreign company having FDI in insurance. That's a very easy

01:53:07.280 --> 01:53:12.600
[Guest]: reform. It's not a complicated reform. When associated with that, you need to do large

01:53:12.600 --> 01:53:18.120
[Guest]: scale improvements in insurance law and the working and the capability of IRDA so that

01:53:18.120 --> 01:53:25.260
[Guest]: these powerful, capable, hungry global insurance companies will not create a consumer protection

01:53:25.260 --> 01:53:29.760
[Guest]: disaster in Indian insurance. That's more difficult because that's like a second generation

01:53:29.760 --> 01:53:34.280
[Guest]: reforms agenda of building state capacity in insurance regulation.

01:53:34.280 --> 01:53:41.760
[Guest]: In the case of agriculture, almost all of it is just get out of the way. So do not interfere

01:53:41.760 --> 01:53:47.240
[Guest]: in international trade. Do not interfere in domestic trade. In the case of the futures

01:53:47.240 --> 01:53:52.600
[Guest]: markets, yes, we do unfortunately need to develop state capacity at SEBI, and that's

01:53:52.600 --> 01:53:56.440
[Guest]: indeed a difficult problem. So we'll have to learn how to become a financial markets

01:53:56.440 --> 01:54:00.960
[Guest]: regulator in an organization like SEBI. We are not there. That is a complicated problem.

01:54:00.960 --> 01:54:05.920
[Guest]: Similarly, in warehousing, all that the government has to do is don't interfere when people hold

01:54:05.920 --> 01:54:10.600
[Guest]: goods in warehouses. This Essential Commodities Act that I'll put you in jail if you have

01:54:10.600 --> 01:54:14.920
[Guest]: inventory of certain things. You know, we need to get out of the way. So a large part

01:54:14.920 --> 01:54:20.280
[Guest]: of the agenda is just get out of the way. For that reason, implementation constraints

01:54:20.280 --> 01:54:27.000
[Guest]: will not be a big problem other than commodity futures, where we need to do the FSLRC agenda

01:54:27.000 --> 01:54:32.920
[Guest]: to get SEBI up to capabilities of stepping away from central planning and achieving high

01:54:32.920 --> 01:54:38.880
[Guest]: rule of law. That is indeed unfinished business in terms of what is happening at SEBI.

01:54:38.880 --> 01:54:44.200
[Guest]: But for the bulk of the agriculture landscape, it's just first generation reforms, freedom,

01:54:44.200 --> 01:54:48.880
[Guest]: freedom, freedom. That's all that's required to be done. It's not difficult to implement.

01:54:48.880 --> 01:54:53.600
[Amit Varma]: And what do you think of the way out of this current imbroglio? Like, you know, the BJP

01:54:53.600 --> 01:54:57.000
[Amit Varma]: messed up the politics of this completely, which is a little bit of a surprise because

01:54:57.000 --> 01:55:01.260
[Amit Varma]: they're normally not that bad at politics, but clearly they didn't foresee this coming

01:55:01.260 --> 01:55:05.560
[Amit Varma]: and they messed it up completely. Now, what's the way out of this? Because on the one hand,

01:55:05.560 --> 01:55:09.560
[Amit Varma]: you have these deep partisan entrenched positions where the government is saying that these

01:55:09.560 --> 01:55:14.360
[Amit Varma]: farmers are anti-nationals, which to me is like, just beyond the pale. And, you know,

01:55:14.360 --> 01:55:19.680
[Amit Varma]: at the same time, that's sort of deepened the resolve of the farmers also. And there's

01:55:19.680 --> 01:55:25.720
[Amit Varma]: a lot of rhetoric and misinformation on all sides. What is a reasonable way out? And is

01:55:25.720 --> 01:55:27.800
[Guest]: there a reasonable way out?

01:55:27.800 --> 01:55:34.760
[Guest]: So I find it heartbreaking that the bills that I consider so aligned with the interests

01:55:34.760 --> 01:55:40.960
[Guest]: of farmers are turning into an angry farmer's movement. The only word I want to use is heartbreaking

01:55:40.960 --> 01:55:46.480
[Guest]: that, you know, how could we come to some place that is so wrong? And I think that we've

01:55:46.480 --> 01:55:51.920
[Guest]: got to go back to basics in terms of the healing, that we've got to rediscover humanity in each

01:55:51.920 --> 01:55:58.080
[Guest]: other. We've got to learn to talk across the aisle. We've got to grow collaboration muscle.

01:55:58.080 --> 01:56:03.520
[Guest]: We've got to grow coordination muscle. We've got to grow negotiation muscle and come back

01:56:03.520 --> 01:56:10.920
[Guest]: into these things in a more quiet environment where the temperature is dialed down and people

01:56:10.920 --> 01:56:15.600
[Guest]: are able to talk to each other in good faith. Because we should see that these bills are

01:56:15.600 --> 01:56:19.560
[Guest]: not the beginning and the end of agricultural reform. There's so much else that's waiting

01:56:19.560 --> 01:56:28.440
[Guest]: to be done. And our ability to do a complex 20-year re-engineering through which India

01:56:28.440 --> 01:56:36.240
[Guest]: becomes an agricultural trade powerhouse and we generate giant gains in production and

01:56:36.240 --> 01:56:44.720
[Guest]: incomes of farmers, that whole process stands to get disrupted if the temperature becomes

01:56:44.720 --> 01:56:52.280
[Guest]: so high. So it seems to me that the need of the hour is really, you know, to be like Gandhiji

01:56:52.280 --> 01:56:59.160
[Guest]: after a horrible episode like Noakhali where you try to bring people together and you say

01:56:59.160 --> 01:57:03.200
[Guest]: that being good to each other is even more important than doing the right things at an

01:57:03.200 --> 01:57:05.880
[Guest]: intellectual and a policy space.

01:57:05.880 --> 01:57:09.360
[Amit Varma]: What does that mean in concrete terms? Does it mean the Modi government going to the farmers

01:57:09.360 --> 01:57:14.360
[Amit Varma]: and saying that, okay, relax, we let it be for now? And what are the demands of the farmers

01:57:14.360 --> 01:57:20.160
[Amit Varma]: that they are not agreeing to? For example, now I haven't studied this in detail. So I'll

01:57:20.160 --> 01:57:24.240
[Amit Varma]: ask you that the farmers apparently wanted a guarantee within the bill that the MSPs

01:57:24.240 --> 01:57:28.000
[Amit Varma]: would continue. Now, in the short term, I don't really see the harm of this because

01:57:28.000 --> 01:57:31.680
[Amit Varma]: as long as you allow trade elsewhere, the MSPs have been there forever, they're going

01:57:31.680 --> 01:57:36.040
[Amit Varma]: to continue to be there if these bills don't pass. So let them be there for a while till

01:57:36.040 --> 01:57:42.680
[Amit Varma]: they are unnecessary, which markets would surely ensure, right? Or is my understanding

01:57:42.680 --> 01:57:43.680
[Guest]: of it flawed?

01:57:43.680 --> 01:57:48.520
[Guest]: I think that when you get temperatures that are this high, there's something deeper that's

01:57:48.520 --> 01:57:54.360
[Guest]: going on. When you and I are engaged in a screaming match, it's not the words that we

01:57:54.360 --> 01:57:59.160
[Guest]: say to each other. There's something else that's going on. It's a deeper estrangement.

01:57:59.160 --> 01:58:03.040
[Guest]: We have lost trust. We've lost confidence in each other. We've lost the presumption

01:58:03.040 --> 01:58:10.240
[Guest]: of good faith. So I actually don't think that there is a need of a discussion around whether

01:58:10.240 --> 01:58:17.880
[Guest]: you should enshrine MSP in the bills or not. What is needed is a hundred episodes where

01:58:17.880 --> 01:58:22.560
[Guest]: people from both sides will break bread with each other and be kind to each other, be good

01:58:22.560 --> 01:58:26.720
[Guest]: to each other and learn to trust each other. It's a process of conversation. It's a process

01:58:26.720 --> 01:58:34.640
[Guest]: of emotionally building bridges and not trying to stake out a power claim this way or that.

01:58:34.640 --> 01:58:40.880
[Guest]: That is the path to building the republic and living with each other in a liberal democracy.

01:58:40.880 --> 01:58:45.160
[Guest]: So as an old saying goes, democracy is the art of living with each other without coming

01:58:45.160 --> 01:58:51.080
[Guest]: to blows. And we have come to blows in this. And in my mind, that is abhorrent. It's more

01:58:51.080 --> 01:58:58.240
[Guest]: important to be civil and be kind to each other than to get economic reforms done.

01:58:58.240 --> 01:59:01.880
[Amit Varma]: That's a fair point. And you know, I buy that point that it's not about this compromise

01:59:01.880 --> 01:59:05.640
[Amit Varma]: or that compromise. It's about the general approach that you take towards each other.

01:59:05.640 --> 01:59:10.480
[Amit Varma]: But there it seems that those bridges have kind of been burned. I mean, it seems to me,

01:59:10.480 --> 01:59:11.480
[Guest]: doesn't it?

01:59:11.480 --> 01:59:16.160
[Guest]: So the solution is then to go back to basics and rebuild those bridges. How do you do that?

01:59:16.160 --> 01:59:22.200
[Guest]: So again, let's go, let's look at the emotional climate around the storming of the Golden

